subject: FW: Parashat Hukat- Turning Off the Cell Phone - Weekly Parasha Insights by Rabbi Eli Mansour
message: I thought this was coincidence.  -----Original Message----- From: Daily Halacha [mailto:return@dailyhalacha.com] Sent: Thursday, July 02, 2009 6:09 AM To: Chave Jacobsohn Subject: Parashat Hukat- Turning Off the Cell Phone - Weekly Parasha Insights by Rabbi Eli Mansour   Weekly Parasha Insights by Rabbi Eli Mansour * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * Description: Parashat Hukat- Turning Off the Cell Phone  The Torah in Parashat Hukat presents the laws relevant to the Para Aduma (red heifer), whose ashes were used to divest people and utensils of their status of Tum'a (ritual contamination).  In this context the Torah discusses the laws of Tum'a that apply to those who are under the same roof as a human corpse.  The Torah writes, "This is the Torah [law] regarding a person who dies in a tent" (19:14).  The Sages of the Talmud noted that this verse may allude to a different concept, as well, namely, the approach we should have toward Torah learning: "Torah is sustained only within one who kills himself over it."  According to this reading, the phrase, "a person who dies in a tent" is the description of how we should go about our Torah study - like someone who "dies in a tent."  What does it mean that one should "kill himself" over Torah, that we should be "dead" in regard to learning?  One explanation is that we should study Torah without any interruption, as though we were "dead."  A dead person does not receive phone calls, cannot attend any meetings, has no access to e-mail, and is not available for consultation.  The Talmud teaches that we should be similarly "dead" with respect to the period allotted for Torah learning.  During that period, we should be no more accessible than a dead person.  That time is sacred, designated exclusively for learning and for nothing else.  Today, this precept has become exceedingly difficult to follow.  Modern technology has given us cell phones and other gadgets that make us accessible at all times, no matter where we are.  Not too long ago, a man in the Bet Midrash could be reached only for emergencies, by calling the nearest payphone.  But today, it is harder than ever to act "dead," to turn off all the communication devices and focus one's attention exclusively on the material one is studying without thinking or worrying about anything else.  I had a morning study partner who was a very successful businessman.  His policy was that he did not answer any phone calls until 1 pm every day. When we finished our learning session and he checked his fourteen or so messages, he discovered that the vast majority of the issues and problems for which he was called in the morning were somehow resolved by 1 pm.  An employee, for example, would call with a frantic problem at 9:00, and at 11:00 he would call back to report that the issue had worked itself out. Had this study partner not turned off his phone for those hours, he would have spent most of the time resolving problems that could have worked themselves out without him.  He understood the importance of "dying in the tent," of making himself "dead" for Torah learning.  Unfortunately, this problem has affected prayer in the synagogue, as well. People find it too difficult to pull themselves away from their communication devices even during prayer services.  All too often we see people in the synagogue checking and sending messages when they are supposed to be focusing on the messages they wish to send to the Almighty.  Let us overcome this challenge and ensure to turn the gadgets off when the time comes to devote our minds to God and to Torah.  These periods of prayer and learning are simply too valuable and precious to waste.  Rather than allow ourselves to be distracted, we must make the most of these opportunities for meaningful and devoted engagement in prayer and study. * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *

subject: FW: Three Men on a Hike
message: Three Men on a Hike  Three men were hiking through a forest when they came upon a large raging, Violent river. Needing to get to the other side, the first man prayed:  'God, please give me the strength to cross the river.'  Poof! .. God gave him big arms and strong legs and he was able to swim across in about 2 hours, having almost drowned twice.  After witnessing that, the second man prayed: 'God, please give me strength and the tools to cross the river'  Poof! .. God gave him a rowboat and strong arms and strong legs and he was able to row across in about an hour after almost capsizing once.  Seeing what happened to the first two men, the third man prayed: 'God,please give me the strength, the tools and the intelligence to cross the river'  Poof! .. He was turned into a woman. She checked the map, hiked one hundred yards up stream and walked across the bridge.  GO AHEAD, SEND THIS TO A WOMAN WHO NEEDS A GOOD LAUGH AND TO ANY MAN WHO CAN HANDLE IT!  'If at first you don't succeed, do it the way your wife told you!'

subject: FW: Taxes
message: This is not about  Democrats or Republicans... it's about both, please                   read. The Tax Poem...... At first I thought this was                   funny....then I realized the awful truth of it. Be sure to                   read all the way to the end.  Tax his land, Tax his bed, Tax the table At which he's fed. Tax his tractor, Tax his mule, Teach him taxes Are the rule. Tax his work, Tax his pay, He works for peanuts Anyway! Tax his cow, Tax his goat, Tax his pants, Tax his coat. Tax his ties, Tax his shirt, Tax his work, Tax his dirt. Tax his tobacco, Tax his drink, Tax him if he Tries to think. Tax his cigars, Tax his eers, If he cries Tax his tears Tax his car, Tax his gas, Find other ways To tax his ass. Tax all he has Then let him know That you won't be done Till he has no dough.  When he screams and hollers; Then tax him some more, Tax him till he's good and sore. Then tax his coffin, Tax his grave, Tax the sod in Which he's laid. Put these words Upon his tomb, Taxes drove me to my doom...' When he's gone, Do not relax, Its time to apply The inheritance tax.  Accounts Receivable Tax Building Permit Tax CDL license Tax Cigarette Tax Corporate Income Tax Dog License Tax Excise Taxes Federal Income Tax Federal Unemployment Tax (FUTA) Fishing License Tax Food License Tax Fuel Permit Tax Gasoline Tax (currently                   44.75 cents per gallon) Gross Receipts Tax Hunting License Tax Inheritance Tax Inventory Tax  IRS Interest Charges IRS   Penalties (tax on top of tax) Liquor Tax Luxury Taxes Marriage License Tax Medicare Tax Personal Property Tax Property Tax Real Estate Tax Service Charge Tax Social Security Tax Road Usage Tax Sales Tax Recreational Vehicle Tax School Tax State Income Tax State Unemployment Tax                   (SUTA) Telephone Federal Excise Tax Telephone Federal Universal Service FeeTax Telephone Federal, State and Local Surcharge Taxes Telephone Minimum Usage Surcharge Tax Telephone Recurring and Non-recurring Charges Tax Telephone State and Local Tax Telephone Usage Charge Tax Utility Taxes Vehicle License Registration Tax Vehicle Sales Tax Watercraft Registration Tax Well Permit Tax Workers Compensation Tax  STILL THINK THIS IS                   FUNNY?  Not one of these taxes existed 100 years ago, and our nation was the most prosperous in the world. We had absolutely no national debt, had the largest middle class in the world, and Mom stayed home to raise the kids.  What in the hell happened?  Can you spell 'politicians?'  And I still have to 'press 1' for English!?  I hope this goes around THE USA at least 100 times!!! YOU can help it get there!!! ? GO AHEAD - - - BE AN AMERICAN!!!

subject: FW: URGENT TEHILLIM READING FOR RABBI KUESSOUS
message: -----Original Message----- From: DailyHalacha [mailto:return@dailyhalacha.com] Sent: Thursday, December 03, 2009 9:27 AM To: Chave Jacobsohn Subject: URGENT TEHILLIM READING FOR RABBI KUESSOUS   We Need Extra Special Tefillot and Mitzvot to Be Taken On for One of the Extra Special Leaders of Our Community:  Rabbi Moshe Kuessous Shlita- Moshe ben Luna (Menahel of Yeshivat Shaare Torah )   The Rabbi was found very recently to have a condition that is as we know of major concern.  Major Community Wide Tehilim Reading & Classes will be Held  1) December 3rd 10:30am -Ahi Ezer - OP & Ave. S. ~Woman Only~ 2) December 3rd 1:00pm-Ohel Simha(Park Ave Shul)~Woman Only~ 3) December 4th Minha 3:45pm -Ohel Simha- (Park Ave Shul)  Rabbi Kuessous is scheduled for Surgery THIS FRIDAY DEC. 4TH.   We know Hashem wants our tefillot and teshuba and we know Hashem yitbarach is all merciful especially when, we, His Children, pour out our hearts and move mountains to take on a new mitzvah or work on a middah.  The Rabbi has done so much for many of us on a personal level and for our children over many years.  IF WE EVER WANTED TO GIVE BACK, WE PROBABLY NEVER THOUGHT WE  COULD COME CLOSE TO WHAT HE HAS DONE FOR US - NOW IS OUR CHANCE.   THE FAMILY IS REQUESTING THAT WE DO EVERYTHING WE CAN AND THAT WE LET EVERYONE KNOW.   You are subscribed using: chave@designsbyfmc.com  To be removed from our members list please click here. Thank you. http://DailyHalacha.com/Unsubscribe.aspx

The tracking # is: 858061503539, so you can go  online to see where your package is holding.  Also, I stuck in an  envelope for my parents, if you could try to drop it off by them  whenever you get a chance (its nothing dachuf), the address is on the  outside, and you've been there a bunch of times... so that would be  great.  I will send pictures of Sima soon, iyh.  If you need anything else, be in touch! message: Dear YAMGJJ,  Your email validation code is 20945  To validate your email address, first return to your PokerStars program.  Go to the main lobby screen (the first screen that appears when you start your program), and select "Account" from the top menu.  Choose the "Validate Email Address ..." menu item. from_: Brooklyn College Office of the Registrar <smart@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Your Undergraduate Advisement/Registration
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN,  Make Your Priority Registration Appointment Today!  You are invited to use Brooklyn College's Self-Managed Appointment Registration Tool (SMART) to select your priority in-person registration appointment.   Priority appointments are designed to give you the courses and support you need to ensure a successful and enjoyable start to your BC education. Classes fill quickly, and the sooner you register, the more flexibility you will have in your course schedule.=A0=20  Please note that you must FIRST satisfy your immunization requirement in order to schedule a registration appointment. If you are not sure you have met the immunization requirement please contact the Health Programs/Immunization Requirements Office immediately.  The Health Programs/Immunization Requirements office is located in room 0710 James Hall and can be reached by phone at (718) 951-4505, by email at hpo@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or by fax at (718) 951-4278.  You will be eligible to schedule a registration appointment on SMART 48 hours after satisfying your immunization requirement.=20 =A0=A0 SMART is available right now! Follow these instructions to schedule your priority appointment today:  1) Go to http://portal.brooklyn.edu 2) Create a new WebCentral account - if you do not already have one - by clicking the "New Users" button at the top of the page. 3) Login with your WebCentral ID and Password. 4) Click the "Schedule or View an Appointment" button located in the "SMART - Registration Appointment" channel in the top of the right column of the Welcome tab. 5) New students should also read the "Getting Started" section.  It provides a nice overview of useful information.=20  Need help with SMART?  Email smart@brooklyn.cuny.edu  or call the Registration Appointment Help Line at (718) 951-5020.=20  Students with disabilities who require accommodations for registration should contact the Center for Student Disability Services, 138 Roosevelt Hall, (718) 951-5538, prior to their registration appointment.=20                 *** Why In-person Registration?  How Does It Work? ***=20  Careful planning is of vital importance to academic success. All incoming degree-seeking first-semester freshmen and incoming transfer students are required to register in person, by appointment only, in order to receive advisement.  Your time is valuable, and in-person processing helps BC ensure that you have everything you need in one easy visit.   Your registration process will take approximately three hours, so please plan accordingly.=A0 During this time, you will attend a half-hour workshop, meet with an advisor in a group setting to plan a balanced course load, and register for your courses.=A0 You must attend all facets of the registration process in order to register for courses.=20  =20                *** Tuition Bills and Financial Aid Information ***=20  After registering for your courses, you will receive a printed copy of your tuition bill and your photo ID card.=20  Please note that paper bills are not mailed. If you misplace your bill you may obtain your account statement via BC's WebCentral portal or at the Enrollment Services Center (ESC) located on the first floor of the West Quad Building.  Please log on to http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay for detailed billing and payment information.=20  Be sure to file your federal FAFSA form and apply for financial aid as soon as possible since processing requires time. For information or assistance, please visit the Financial Aid section at http://portal.brooklyn.edu. Note that a FAFSA is not only needed for financial aid, but also for many scholarships.  Failure to pay tuition and fees by the due date could result in the cancellation of registration.                 *** Payment Due Dates ***=20 INITIAL REGISTRATION=09=09PAYMENT DUE December 8 - 29 =09=09=09January 7 December 30 - January 11=09January 14 January 12 - 20=09=09=09January 21 After January 20=09=09=09Immediately Upon Registration   Tuition Liability Schedule:=20 0% liability=09=09Drop prior to January 28 25% liability=09=09Drop January 28-February 3 50% liability=09=09Drop February 4-10 75% liability=09=09Drop February 11-17 100% liability=09=09Drop February 18 and thereafter  We look forward to seeing you at registration, and having you as part of the Brooklyn College Community.=20

subject: Student Immunization Requirements
message: Your immunization records are incomplete, and therefore you are not compliant with New York State Public Health Law.    Without submitting proof of immunization, you WILL NOT BE ABLE TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT TO REGISTER.   Immunization records will not be collected at the registration site.   You must submit your records 2 business days prior to your registration appointment.   To be compliant you must submit the following:  - Proof of two doses of Measles vaccination, one dose of Mumps vaccination, and one dose of Rubella vaccination OR proof of a combined MMR vaccination.   - Completed Meningitis Response Form. For form:  http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/pub/immunization.htm    Submit your records to the Office of Immunization and Health Programs:  - In person in room 0710 James Hall  - By fax at 718.951.4278 (available 24 hours every day)  - Scanned into email and sent to hpo@brooklyn.cuny.edu  - By US Mail addressed to: Office of Immunization and Health Programs, Room 0710 James Hall, Brooklyn College, 2900 Bedford Avenue, Brooklyn, New York, 11210. (Must be received 2 business days prior to your registration appointment.)   For more information please call 718.951.4505 or email hpo@brooklyn.cuny.edu .  Please remember, YOU WILL NOT BE ABLE TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT TO REGISTER if you are not immunization compliant.  You will be eligible to use SMART to schedule a registration appointment 48 hours after satisfying your immunization requirement.

message: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN,  Thank you for using SMART.  You have made an appointment as a first semester freshman student to register for courses on:   Jan  8 2010 11:00AM in the West Quad Building  Your appointment confirmation number is: 8319398191  Please be advised, except for special circumstances no one other than the student who is registering will be permitted to enter the registration area.   During your appointment you will attend a workshop, meet with an advisor in a group setting, and schedule your classes for Spring 2010 semester. The entire registration process can take up to 3 hours, so please plan accordingly.  Please bring with you:   A printout of this confirmation. This is your admission slip to the registration site. You may not be admitted if you are not on the session roster.    A pen.   A method of payment (cash, check, money order, major credit card).   Any student copies of Advanced Placement Scores, College Now transcripts, or current college transcripts.    Please remember that your immunization must be cleared 2 business days prior to your registration appointment. If you are not immunization compliant at the time of your appointment, you will not be allowed to register. Immunization records will not be collected at the registration site. subject: Spring 2010 Tuition Payment Reminder
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Thank you for registering for the Spring 2010 semester. Your tuition payment for the Spring semester is due on January  14, 2010. According to our records, your account reflects an outstanding balance. Please make arrangements to settle your bill by the bill due date. Failure to do so may result in the cancellation of your courses. Please note that a partial financial aid award does not consititute full payment and will not secure your classes. You are responsible for any balance that remains after financial aid is applied to your bill.   You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). You may also make full payment online using an electronic funds transfer at no cost, or a credit card through WebCentral. VISA cards are not accepted. There is a 2.65% convenience fee associated with the use of all credit or debit cards.    You can access a list of payment options at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay.  For further information, please call 718-758-8150, e-mail us at esc@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad building. If you feel that you have received this e-mail in error, please feel free to e-mail us or contact us over the phone.   The Enrollment Services Center will be open the following regular hours: Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. - 10 p.m. Friday:                   9 a.m. -  6 p.m. Saturday and Sunday:      9 a.m. -  5 p.m.    For phone assistance, please contact the Enrollment Services Call Center during the following hours:  Monday - Thursday        9 a.m. -  7:45 p.m.  Friday                   9 a.m. - 4:45 p.m. Saturday and Sunday      Closed      Thank you,   The Enrollment Services Center Team   		This email was sent to: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN <jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com>

subject: Free Tax Preparation
message: Dear Members of the Brooklyn College Community:  Hope all is well and best wishes for a happy and healthy New Year.   It is my pleasure and privilege to announce a new on campus service being offered to the College Community - the VITA program (Volunteer Income Tax Assistance).  This program will be offered in Whitehead Hall beginning February 2010 and shall end April 2010.  The dates and times are as follows:   FRIDAY  10 am to 8 pm  SATURDAY  10 am to 8 pm  SUNDAY  10 am to 9 pm   Rooms 201 Whitehead and the Investment Library at Whitehead  (Additional Days may be Offered)  We shall also provide free E-filing and direct deposit.  For more information and/or questions, please feel free to contact us at BrooklyncollegeVITA@gmail.com.  In addition, please feel free to announce this to your friends and family members who may also wish to have their taxes prepared by a member of our VITA program.  Thanks in advance for your assistance and cooperation.    Cordially, Alexander K. Buchholz Deputy VITA Coordinator abuchholz@brooklyn.cuny.edu   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: College Relief Efforts in Haiti
message: The Office of Diversity and Equity Programs will be collecting the supplies to donate to a group of doctors and healthcare workers leaving for Haiti this weekend.    Please bring all donations to their office, 2147 Boylan Hall, by Friday, February 15, before 5 p.m.  The following items are most needed:   Medical: Band Aids, Iodine, Splints, Alcohol, Bandages, Sutra kits, Advil/Tylenol, vitamins Food: granola bars, candies, energy bars and other small non perishables Baby items: baby clothes, bottles, blankets, diapers, anything that a child or baby might need  Other items: mosquito spray, feminine products (pads, underwear, t-shirts, blankets, socks)   Other ways you can help:  - Cash donations may be deposited in the Brooklyn College Disaster Relief Fund, located in Central Depository, Room 302, Student Center. Funds will be remitted to the American Red Cross for Haiti.   Checks must be made payable to the American Red Cross.   - Cell phone users can text "Haiti" to 90999 and $10 will go to relief efforts in Haiti. The $10 will show up on your phone bill.*    If you are organizing a relief effort, contact Dave Bryan, Coordinator of Disaster Relief Efforts, at Dbryan@brooklyn.cuny.edu or call 718.951.5352.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Earthquake in Haiti and Brooklyn College Relief Efforts
message: Dear Brooklyn College Community:  We have all been shocked and deeply saddened by the tragic event in Haiti. Our hearts go out to the students, faculty and staff who have loved ones and friends there.  At the request of Chancellor Matthew Goldstein, CUNY is organizing a response initiative, under the leadership of Peter Grant Jordan, Interim Vice-Chancellor for Student Affairs, to support local relief activities and humanitarian efforts.   Our campus representative for this effort is Dave Bryan, Special Assistant to the Dean of Student Affairs. We will also be reaching out to the leadership of the Haitian community in Brooklyn, to offer any assistance that can be helpful, and to lend our support. Information and updates will be posted on the Brooklyn College website.  Karen L. Gould  President  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Thank You for Your Help--Haiti Relief Efforts
message: We would like to thank the Brooklyn College community for coming together to support the Haitian relief activities. Students, staff, faculty and community members donated enough much-needed medical and first-aid supplies, food and clothing to fill four vans for NOVA Hope for Haiti. We wish to extend a special thank you to the volunteers, especially leaders of several student organizations, who met in the Office of Diversity and Equity Programs to help sort, box and transport the donations. It is truly amazing what a group of committed volunteers can accomplish in such a short period of time!   Members of the college community can continue to donate to the American Red Cross Haiti relief efforts via Central Depository, third floor, Student Center.   New entering students will have an opportunity to contribute during the Orientation programs for freshmen and transfer students on Wednesday, January 20, and graduate students on Thursday, January 21, in the Student Center.   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: BAR Notice - Avoid Cancellation of your Spring 2010 Registration
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Your Spring 2010 semester tuition payment is  past due. According to our records, your account reflects an outstanding balance. A BAR has been placed on your account. Payment is due immediately in order to secure your classes.       You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). You may also make full payment online using an electronic funds transfer at no cost, or a credit card through WebCentral. VISA cards are not accepted. There is a 2.65% convenience fee associated with the use of all credit or debit cards.  .    You can access a list of payment options at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay.  For further information, please call 718-758-8150, e-mail us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad building. If you feel that you have received this e-mail in error, please feel free to e-mail us or contact us over the phone. from_: BC in China Study Abroad Program <CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Open House: Study Abroad in China
message: Open House: Study Abroad in China =20  Times:=20  1. 12:30 - 1:30 pm, Tuesday, February 2, 2010=20  2. 12:30 - 1:30 pm, Wednesday, February 3, 2010  3. 12:30 - 1:30 pm, Tuesday, February 9, 2010  Place:  3439 Boylan Hall, Brooklyn College  =20  Come and learn about an inexpensive way to travel and study in China:=20  See the new Beijing and the new China after the Olympics  Enjoy Shanghai World Expo 2010 (May to October 2010)  =20  Summer Study Abroad in China, Tentative Dates: May 27-June 23, 2010   One-Month Program to Five Famous Chinese Cities:  Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou & Shanghai  With side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain, Tibet  Check the program's website (photos, comments, FAQ's, etc. ) for details at:=20  http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china/  =20  Students may choose 3-6 credits of study from the following:  1. History 53: Revolutionary China=20  2. Core 20.06: Development of the Silk Road=20  3. Business 76.5: Asian Business=20  4. Chinese 1.1: Beginners Chinese; Chinese 2.1: Intermediate Chinese=20  5. Speech 18.5: Intercultural Communication=20  6. Speech 23: Business & Professional Communication (cross-cultural perspectives)=20  =20  Program Features:  - All courses are taught by Brooklyn College faculty, for CUNY-BC credit=20  - Group travel to 5 most famous and beautiful Chinese cities: Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou & Shanghai=20  - Field trips to sites of historical and cultural importance (e.g., TianAnMen Square, the Great Wall, Forbidden City, Summer Palace, Terra Cotta Warriors, Ancient City Walls, Buddhist Temples, Jewish Synagogue, Great Islamic Mosques, Suzhou Gardens, Silk Factory, Cloisonn=E9 Factory, the Bund, etc)=20  - Experience Chinese culture, interact with local people, have a real feel of Chinese life=20  - Travel and sightseeing are arranged by professional travel agencies=20  - Side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain or Tibet=20 =20  Total Estimated Program Cost: only $2,898, which includes:  a. round-trip international tickets (NYC to Beijing; Shanghai to NYC)=20  b. transportation within and between the Chinese cities=20  c. nice hotels in all the cities in China=20  d. admission tickets to the scenic spots=20   Application Deadline: March 12, 2010 (first come first serve)  Eligibility:  1. CUNY undergraduate and graduate=20  2. Students from any other colleges in the U.S.; and=20  3. CUNY faculty, staff and alumni=20  =20  STOCS scholarships and financial Aid are available for qualified students.   For more information about the program,=20  1. Visit the program website: http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china  2. E-mail Professor Lu at CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu , or  3. Call 718-951-5225 (ask for Ms. Sonia Garrick)  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Fall 2009 BC Feedback Results
message: Dear Students,  We would like to thank all of you who took the time to respond to the Fall 2009 BC Feedback (Student Evaluation of the Faculty) questionnaires!  Your responses to the fixed-choice questions and your thoughtful comments are invaluable for enhancing teaching and learning at Brooklyn College.   Those of you who completed all of your evaluations last semester can now access the BC Feedback results for Fall 2009.  They are available under the "Academics" tab on the WebCentral portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu).  For others, you can review previous semesters' results at the same location.    As promised, students who completed all of their evaluations were automatically entered into a raffle for $500 in prizes. The 1st prize winner will receive a gift card for $250, the second $100, and three students will each receive $50.  All prize winners will be notified by mail in the next week.  Thank you again for your participation!  We take your evaluations very seriously.    Sincerely,   Jerry Mirotznik Associate Provost         ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Residence Hall nearing completion!
message: Did you know that an exciting new residence facility exclusively for BC students is nearing completion two blocks from campus?  The new facility on the corner of Kenilworth Place and Farragut Road, is anticipated to be available for occupancy for the Fall 2010 semester.  It will house up to 290 students in 220 full-furnished units of varying configurations, including:  Two Bedroom - three students with one shared room and one private room  Two Bedroom with private entrances - two students with two private rooms Studio Apartment - either one or two students (shared or private)  The rent amount will include all utilities and a broad range of amenities.  Unit Amenities:  * Bathroom * Kitchenette * Wi-fi internet * Cable TV * Large window * Air conditioning   Building-wide Amenities: * Laundry facilities * Proximity key access * 24 hour security * Meeting and study rooms * Exercise room * Outdoor Terrace * Courtyard * Lounges   Brooklyn College will also provide security and transportation to and from campus.  Please note that space is limited and demand will be strong, so the earlier you apply, the better.  To be considered for a place in the Residence Hall, please register your interest online using the Residence Hall tool, under the eServices tab of the BC WebCentral Portal.      ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: PokerStars Support - Cash out Options
message: Hello Avraham,  Thank you for writing to us for more information. It is always good  to understand your options to find the one that is best for you.   Players from the US may cash out via any of the following methods:  - Instant eChecks   An eCheck is an electronic check which allows you to make safe,  secure and immediate electronic fund transfers (EFT) directly from  your bank account to your PokerStars account.   Funds deposited via eCheck are immediately available in your  PokerStars account even though the funds are not received from your  bank account instantly. For more information about eChecks, please  visit http://www.pokerstars.com/poker/real-money/echecks/.   Once you have made an eCheck deposit which has cleared, you may  choose to receive your funds credited back to your bank account on  the Cash Out screen.   - Checks   If you would like to receive a check directly from PokerStars, we  process them five times per week (Monday through Friday).    The minimum you can request on any one check is $25 and the maximum  is $2,500.   All checks, regardless of the amount, are sent by First-Class Mail -  we do not deliver checks via UPS or FedEx or any other courier  service. Please note that First-Class mail does not come with  tracking numbers for their deliveries, so we cannot provide tracking  data for your checks. Please allow 15 business days for the check to  arrive to your registered mailing address.  You can read more about our checks withdrawal option at  http://www.pokerstars.com/poker/real-money/checks/.   - Wires   Wire transfer cashouts to your US bank account are available via the  PokerStars Cashier for a minimum of $1,000.   Fill in your bank account details, submit your request, and within  72 business hours it should be processed on our end. Once completed,  please allow 3 to 5 business days the funds to appear in your bank  account.   PokerStars covers all fees charged by the sending bank, but you may  be charged a fee by your bank and by an intermediary bank (if  applicable) for receiving a wire transfer. For more information on  your bank's policy concerning fees for receiving wire transfers,  please contact your bank directly.  For more details on our cashout policy, please visit:  http://www.pokerstars.com/poker/real-money/cashouts/  If you have other questions, please do not hesitate in contacting  us.    Regards,  Magda PokerStars Support Team   ----- Original Message ----- From: jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com Sent: 2010/02/01 12:19:02 To: support@pokerstars.com Subject: Cashing Out  >User ID: YAMGJJ        This message was sent from the Contact  Support form. subject: Willard and Eleanor Archie Professional Skills Training Program
message: Dear Student,   The Willard and Eleanor Archie Professional Skills Training Program at Brooklyn College is designed to prepare students for the competition they will face in their careers. At the workshops students will develop the skills and attitudes most often cited by employers as leading to career mobility and productivity, such as, communication, team work, leadership, critical thinking, working in a diverse environment, etc.  These workshops/panels are facilitated by professionals, alumni and experts in their fields.  Refreshments will be provided.    Sign-up for all workshops by logging onto BC WebCentral (http://portal.brooklyn.cuny.edu and select the Career Tab)  For each event we will give away a free book on the topic to the 1st 25 pre-registered students that attend.    The Future:  The Skills and Job Trends of the New Decade Guest Speaker:  Garry Golden, Futurist  Tuesday, March 9th 12:30 - 2:00pm Gold Room, Student Center  What are the future trends in technology and communications that will affect your future?  What is a Social Entrepreneur and how can you create a successful career as one?  Our guest speaker Garry Golden holds a degree in Futurist Studies and can help guide you through the forecasts of what to expect in the post recession world.   Networking with Others to Succeed Guest Speaker:  Sharon Barnes, 1010 Wins News Radio  Friday, March 12th 10:30am - 11:30am Alumni Lounge, Student Center  As it is often said finding and keeping a job is determined by whom you know.  Being connected to the right people certainly increases you chances for success in the job search and in your career.  This workshop will help you identify who is in your network (and yes you have a network), learn how to network effectively and how not using your network will negatively impact you.    10 Things Employers Want You to Learn in College Guest Speaker:  Prof. Bill Coplin, Syracuse University Professor and Author  Tuesday, April 13th 12:30 - 2:00pm Maroon Room, Student Center  Do you have the skills needed for college and career success?  Do you know what employers look for in candidates?  What do you need to know to become more professional in the workforce?  Author Bill Coplin will discuss the top ten things students should learn now instead of learning it the hard way in the real world.     Secrets of the Highly Successful  Guest Speakers:  Jeffrey Fried - Lawyer/Sports Agent, Fried & Co. P.C.; Edwin Cohen - Real Estate Broker, Prism Capital Partners LLC;  Karen Berger - Executive Editor, DC Comics Vertigo Imprint  Tuesday, April 20th        12:30 p.m. - 2:00 pm          Gold Room, Student Center  Brooklyn College alumni who have achieved the highest level of success in their career are coming back to share their secrets of success.  Do you aspire to own your company or one day be the head of a company?  Do you have questions on what it takes to get there?  This panel of illustrious alumni will surely help you get on your way to achieving your career success.      You're Graduating....Now What? Guest Speakers:  Alumni Panelists will include representatives from CBS, PWC, Target and other recognizable companies.  Tuesday, May 4th           12:30 - 2:00                        Jefferson/Williams, Student Center  College is finally over...now what?  Its time to get out into the real world and apply your hard earned degree.  Learn from recent graduates about what to expect and how to strive for stability and success.   Hear recent alumni share their stories of transitioning from college to their first "real" job.  Ask them questions about what employers expect and what it takes to be successful.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: The Community's Response to the Earthquake in Haiti
message: Welcome back to campus.=20  As you are aware, the nation of Haiti was struck by a deadly earthquake on January 12. The impact of this tragedy and its devastation has hit home for many of us, including students, faculty and staff of Brooklyn College (BC) who are part of the Haitian Diaspora, many of whom have received sorrowful news about loved ones and friends.  The world has responded quickly to aid the people of Haiti. At the request of Chancellor Matthew Goldstein, CUNY has organized a university-wide response to coordinate activities and share information. Brooklyn College has designated Dave Bryan, special assistant to the dean of Student Affairs, to serve as our campus relief coordinator. To date, several relief activities and community-sponsored events have occurred or will take place on campus:  * Nearly $3,000 was collected by the Brooklyn College Haitian American Students Association (HASA), the Inter-Greek Council, BC Cheerleaders, and through walk-in individual donations to the Central Depository for the American Red Cross and Y=E9le.  * Medical supplies, clothing, school supplies and food were collected by HASA, the Office of Affirmative Action and Diversity Compliance and the Haitian Bilingual/ESL Assistance Center (HABETAC).  * On February 4, Assemblymember Rhoda Jacobs and Councilman Dr. Mathieu Eugene, in conjunction with the Children Foundation for Help in Haiti, Inc., organized a "Gathering in Solidarity" in support of the Haitian Community. The event was held at the Walt Whitman Theater and was hosted by the Office Diversity and Equity Programs and the Golden Key International Honour Society of Brooklyn College.  * HASA, the BC Chapter of the American Red Cross, the Black Students Union and the Caribbean Students Union hosted a Haiti Relief Awareness, "EDE AYITI: HELP HAITI" on February 4.  * The Beraca Baptist Church, located at 9602 Flatlands Avenue, Brooklyn, NY 11236, is raising funds for health care, crisis counseling, rescue and recovery, and reconstruction. Call 718.257.1000, ext. 306.  * President Obama has designated Haitians for Temporary Protected Status (TPS), which is valid for eighteen months and will allow eligible Haitians an opportunity to obtain work authorization. TPS is available to Haitian nationals who were present in the U.S. as of January 12, 2010, and are continuously residing in the U.S.  Qualified individuals have until July 20, 2010 to apply for TPS.  The Legal Aid Society has been identified by New York City as one of the key organizations to assist eligible Haitian immigrants in receiving TPS. The Society's Immigration Law Unit has set up a Haitian TPS Hotline. Call 888.284.2772, or visit the website at www.legal-aid.org . You may also contact the office of Assemblywoman Rhoda Jacobs at 718.434.0446 for more information.  The work of assisting the people of Haiti is ongoing. Throughout the semester, we will continue to engage in relief-related activities and assist members of the campus community who are of Haitian descent or who have family in Haiti.  Students in need of personal or academic support for a range of issues, including tuition and other financial matters, should contact Student Assistance and Referral, 2106 Boylan Hall, 718.951.5352, studentsar@brooklyn.cuny.edu.  Counseling services are available for students, faculty and staff at the Personal Counseling Program, located at 0203 James Hall, 718.951.5363, or visit http://pc.brooklyn.cuny.edu/.  To share or receive information about upcoming Haitian relief activities on campus, please contact Dave Bryan at 718.951.5352, or e-mail dbyran@brooklyn.cuny.edu.  Regular updates will be posted on the BC WebCentral Portal, https://portal.brooklyn.edu, and the college Facebook page, http://www.facebook.com/pages/Brooklyn-NY/Brooklyn-College/111090580325?ref=3Dts.  The sensitivity and generosity of the Brooklyn College community have made a difference both in our borough and on the Republic of Haiti.  These goodwill efforts will surely continue this semester and in the future.   Karen L. subject: City-based and Sustainability Education - FREE LUNCHES
message: Dear Brooklyn College Student  Are you looking for hands-on experiences that teach problem solving in the "real world"?  If your answer is "yes," please join us in a series of events that highlight innovative campus programs that use the borough as a classroom. The Provost's Task Force on City-Based and Sustainability Education is sponsoring a number of events this semester to provide opportunities for faculty and students who want to learn how they can teach and learn in the borough.  Our first event is on February 16th from 12:30 to 2:00. We welcome you to lunch to hear how faculty from the Sociology Department have incorporated city-based learning and sustainability into their classes. Students from these classes will also share how these experiences enriched their learning. Lunch will be provided. Honors Academy Seminar Room, 2231 Boylan Hall. RSVP: tmulqueen@brooklyn.cuny.edu  Mark your calendar for upcoming events and look for details in Brooklyn Mornings:   Wednesday, March 3rd, 5:30-7:30, Town Hall on City-Based and Sustainability Education   Friday, March 19th, 11:00-1:15, meet community partners at Brooklyn Botanic Garden   Tuesday, March 23rd, 12:30-2:00, student forum and discussion on city-based education and sustainability education   Friday, April 16th, 9:00am-11:00am, Walking Tour of Religious Institutions in Flatbush  We look forward to seeing you there,  Professor Tammy Lewis Professor Jocelyn Wills Dean Donna Wilson    ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

from_: "Jennifer S. Rubain, Office of Diversity and Equity Programs" <jrubain@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Take the BC Diversity Climate Survey - Win Prizes!
message: The Diversity and Inclusion Plan Implementation Committee is evaluating the college's efforts to create a diverse and inclusive environment.  Unless otherwise specified, diversity is broadly defined as a range of differences among people in terms of age, ethnicity, family background, gender, language, learning styles, level of academic preparedness, national origin, physical or mental abilities, race, religion, sexual orientation, and socioeconomic status.       Keeping this definition in mind, we ask that you complete the survey below, which assesses attitudes and experiences related to diversity issues on campus.  This survey is completely anonymous and participation is voluntary!  You may choose to answer all, some, or none of the questions.   We hope, however, that you will choose to fully participate because your input is valuable and helps us assess the current campus climate and plan future initiatives.  Participants may enter a RAFFLE once the survey is completed for a chance to win a Kindle Wireless Reading Device, $200 gift card, BC parking pass, BC gym membership, and many smaller prizes!  Raffle winners will be notified on March 1, 2010.    If you have questions about this survey, please contact Jennifer Rubain, director of diversity and equity programs, at jrubain@brooklyn.cuny.edu or 718.951.4128.     We will present the results of the survey in a Town Hall meeting this semester.   To begin the survey, click below and enter the username guest:  https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/diversity/students     ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Free Student Midweek and Weekend Technology Workshops
message: The Office of Academic Information Technologies (AIT) presents intensive,  hands-on technology workshops designed to introduce you to the most  useful skills for the Spring semester =20  =20  There is NO registration necessary, simply come by for any of the topics you  are interested in!  Workshops and all materials are FREE!   Open to ALL  members of the campus community!    Midweek Series  =20  Spreadsheets are the easiest, quickest way to store any type of encapsulated data, such as  names, addresses, grades, dollar values and the like. Starting with an analysis of the screen  elements, we will build a complete simple project, look at advanced features like formula   construction and graphing, and end by creating a very useful financial-based, user-defined  application.  Spreadsheets with Microsoft Excel, Part 1  Tue., Feb. 23  3:40PM-4:55PM  Library, Room 120  =20   Repeated  Wed., Feb. 24  5:05PM-6:20PM  Library, Room 384  =20  Spreadsheets with Microsoft Excel, Part 2=20  Tue., Mar. 2  3:40PM-4:55PM  Library, Room 120               =20  Repeated           =20  Wed., Mar. 3   5:05PM-6:20PM   Library, Room 120  =20  Spreadsheets with Microsoft Excel, Part 3  Tue., Mar. 9  3:40PM-4:55PM  Library, Room 120  =20  Repeated  Wed., Mar. 10   5:05PM-6:20PM  Library, Room 122  =20   Analysis of raw numerical data has never been easier than with SPSS. SPSS organizes your   kernel numbers and maintains a complete library of formulas for you to use. In these  workshops, we will examine SPSS' unusual interface, analyze several sets of numbers, import   raw data from other applications, and conclude with an interesting real-world analytical   problem  Statistical Analysis with SPSS, Part 1                        =20  Tue., Mar. 16  3:40PM-4:55PM  Library, Room 120  =20  Repeated  Wed., Mar. 17  5:05PM-6:20PM  Library, Room 120  =20  Statistical Analysis with SPSS, Part 2 NEW!       =20  Tue., Mar. 23  3:40PM-4:55PM  Library, Room 120  =20  Repeated  Wed., Mar. 24  5:05PM-6:20PM  Library, Room 122  =20  PowerPoint is an indispensable tool for today's public speakers. subject: Welcome to Windows Live ID
message: Hello jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com,  Thank you for signing up for a Windows Live ID.  Use the e-mail address (jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com) and password you provided during sign-up to sign in at any site or service where you see the Windows Live ID logo.  This e-mail message contains important information on how to use your account, including what to do if you forget your password. Please save or print a copy so you can refer to it later.  TO SIGN IN Click the sign in link at any participating site, and then type your e-mail address and password in the sign in box.  You can also sign in with a single click, by choosing to save your e-mail address and password on your computer when you sign in.  TO SIGN OUT Click the sign-out link at any participating site to sign out of all Windows Live ID sites.  OTHER IMPORTANT LINKS  You can sign into Account Services from the Windows Live ID home page at:  https://accountservices.passport.net/?lc=1033  At Account Services you can see more useful information, and view or change your profile.  IF YOU FORGET YOUR PASSWORD You can reset your password at Account Services. We strongly recommend choosing a question and a secret answer, and an alternate e-mail address where you can have Windows Live ID send you a password reset message. To create these password safeguards, go to the Credentials page of Account Services.  To reset your password, go to Account Services, click Forgot Your Password, and follow the instructions on the screen.  Windows Live ID is committed to protecting your privacy. We encourage you to review the Privacy Statement at  https://accountservices.passport.net/PPPrivacyStatement.srf?lc=1033  If you have questions regarding the Privacy Statement, send an e-mail message to passpriv@microsoft.com.  To request more help, contact Customer Support at https://accountservices.passport.net/CustomerSupport.srf?lc=1033.  Thank you for using Windows Live ID! subject: Financial Aid: Dropping or Withdrawing From Classes
message: A common concern of students when dropping or withdrawing from their classes is how will this affect my financial aid eligibility? In other words, will I still be eligible for financial aid and will I have to pay anything to the college?  If you dropped before or on February 17th you are not eligible for any federal aid.  Tuition liability (the percentage of your bill that you are liable for once the first day of classes begins) began on January 28th. The liability schedule for the Spring 2010 semester is as follows:   Spring 2010 Schedule of Tuition Refund and Student Liability 0% Liability	Drop prior to January 28 25% Liability	Drop January 28-February 3 50% Liability	Drop February 4-10 75% Liability	Drop February 11-17 100% Liability	Withdraw February 18 and thereafter    For example, if you dropped a class between Jan 28th - Feb 3rd, you would be responsible for 25% of your tuition cost plus tuition fees. After Feb. 18th and thereafter, you will be able to withdraw from classes with a W grade but you would be 100% liable for the cost of your tuition.  NOTE: A WN grade is given to students who never began attendance in a course. If so; the student will be considered to not have earned any Title IV aid. Students will be liable for the tuition.  How does dropping or withdrawing from classes affect my federal financial aid?  If you drop/withdraw from some or all of your courses before April 5th, your federal financial aid may be affected. The federal funds that are affected are listed below in the order of how they are affected:  * Unsubsidized Stafford Loans * Subsidized Stafford Loans * Perkins Loans * Graduate PLUS Loan * Parent PLUS Loan * Pell Grant * Academic Competiveness Grant (ACG) * National SMART Grant * TEACH Grant   Financial aid is calculated based on the percentage of studies that have been completed. For example, if you have completed 30 percent of the days of the term, then you are entitled to 30 percent of the financial aid that you were scheduled to receive calculated on a pro-rated basis. The percentage of aid that you have earned is applied to your tuition and fees but this may not cover your entire tuition obligation. If you have a balance after financial aid is applied, you must remit payment to the college immediately. Once you have completed more than 60 percent of the days in the term, you will have earned all of the aid that you were scheduled to receive for that term.  What will happen if I stop attending classes or do not officially withdraw from classes?  If you leave school during the semester without officially withdrawing, the college will attempt to verify your last date of attendance. Once this is determined, we will determine how much aid you are eligible based on the federal withdrawal calculation.    What if after dropping or withdrawing from classes, I do not have enough aid to cover my tuition obligation?  You must repay the required amount during the term in which you withdraw. Failure to repay the required amount will result in a stop being placed on your records and you will not be able to obtain a transcript or register until repayment is made. If your accounts balance in not settled, your account may be sent to a collection agency.  What if I have earned more financial aid than I initially received?  In some cases, you may be entitled to post-withdrawal funds. A post-withdrawal disbursement is funds that are posted to your account after you have dropped or withdrew from classes. If the post-withdrawal disbursement include loans, written permission is required before we can disburse the funds to you. You may choose to decline some or all of the loan funds to avoid incurring debt.  I decided that I would like to drop or withdraw from classes, what should I do?  You should consult with a financial aid counselor before dropping or withdrawing from classes to determine if a financial obligation will incur. You can speak to a representative from financial aid by calling 718-951-5051 or by visiting the Enrollment Services Center located in the Lobby of the West Quad building.     ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

from_: "Jennifer S. Rubain, Director of Diversity and Equity Programs " <jrubain@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Still Time to Take the BC Diversity Climate Survey - Win Prizes!
message: The Diversity and Inclusion Plan Implementation Committee is evaluating the college's efforts to create a diverse and inclusive environment.  Unless otherwise specified, diversity is broadly defined as a range of differences among people in terms of age, ethnicity, family background, gender, language, learning styles, level of academic preparedness, national origin, physical or mental abilities, race, religion, sexual orientation, and socioeconomic status.       Keeping this definition in mind, we ask that you complete the survey below, which assesses attitudes and experiences related to diversity issues on campus.  This survey is completely anonymous and participation is voluntary!  You may choose to answer all, some, or none of the questions.   We hope, however, that you will choose to fully participate because your input is valuable and helps us assess the current campus climate and plan future initiatives.  Participants may enter a RAFFLE once the survey is completed for a chance to win a Kindle Wireless Reading Device, $200 gift card, BC parking pass, BC gym membership, and many smaller prizes!  Raffle winners will be notified on March 1, 2010.    If you have questions about this survey, please contact Jennifer Rubain, director of diversity and equity programs, at jrubain@brooklyn.cuny.edu or 718.951.4128.     We will present the results of the survey in a Town Hall meeting this semester.   To begin the survey, click below and enter the username guest:  https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/diversity/students   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: We need your support for Open House Event

subject: Announcing the CUNY Math Challenge: Feb 28 registration deadline
message: Dear Brooklyn College Undergraduate Student,  I am pleased to inform you that CUNY is holding its second annual CUNY Math Challenge, a University-wide mathematics competition for all CUNY undergraduates that challenges contestants to solve math problems and puzzles of varying levels of difficulty, developed by a committee of CUNY faculty.  CUNY will award our most creative mathematical minds with cash prizes ranging from $500 to $2,500, funded by the Academic Leadership Award received by Chancellor Goldstein from the Carnegie Corporation of New York.  Interested undergraduates can register online at http://math.cisdd.org.  The first round of problems was opened on February 15. New rounds will begin every other week and participants will have two weeks to submit their answers, accumulating points along the way.  Students with the most points after four rounds will be invited to sit for a final in-person exam to be administered on April 25, 2010.   The deadline for registration is February 28.  You do not have to be a Math major to enter.   Best, Dean Donna Wilson   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Open House: Study Abroad in China
message: 1. 12:30 - 1:30 pm, Thursday, February 25, 2010=20 =20 2. 12:30 - 1:30 pm, Monday, March 1, 2010  3. 12:30 - 1:30 pm, Tuesday, March 2, 2010  Place:  3439 Boylan Hall, Brooklyn College  Come and learn about an inexpensive way to travel and study in China:=20 See the new Beijing and the new China after the Olympics Enjoy Shanghai World Expo 2010 (May to October 2010)  Summer Study Abroad in China, Tentative Dates: May 27-June 23, 2010   One-Month Program to Five Famous Chinese Cities:  Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou & Shanghai  With side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain, Tibet  Check the program's website (photos, comments, FAQ's, etc. ) for details at:=20  http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china/  =20  Students may choose 3-6 credits of study from the following:  1. History 53: Revolutionary China=20  2. Core 20.06: Development of the Silk Road  3. Business 76.5: Asian Business=20  4. Chinese 1.1: Beginners Chinese; Chinese 2.1: Intermediate Chinese=20  5. Speech 18.5: Intercultural Communication=20  6. Speech 23: Business & Professional Communication (cross-cultural perspectives)=20  7. CC1.1 Classical Cultures (China)  =20  Program Features:  -All courses are taught by Brooklyn College faculty, for CUNY-BC credit  -Group travel to 5 most famous and beautiful Chinese cities: Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou & Shanghai=20  -Field trips to sites of historical and cultural importance (e.g., TianAnMen Square, the Great Wall, Forbidden City, Summer Palace, Terra Cotta Warriors, Ancient City Walls, Buddhist Temples, Jewish Synagogue, Great Islamic Mosques, Suzhou Gardens, Silk Factory, Cloisonn=E9 Factory, the Bund, etc)=20  -Experience Chinese culture, interact with local people, have a real feel of Chinese life=20  -Travel and sightseeing are arranged by professional travel agencies=20  -Side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain or Tibet=20 =20  Enjoy the beautiful Shanghai as host of World Expo 2010 (May to October 2010) - http://en.expo2010.cn/  Video: Click here for City Rhapsody: A Preview of the Site of Expo Shanghai - http://en.expo2010.cn/sr/video/shipin2.htm  =20  Total Estimated Program Cost: only $2,898, which includes:  a.        round-trip international tickets (NYC to Beijing; Shanghai to NYC)=20 b.        transportation within and between the Chinese cities=20 c.        nice hotels in all the cities in China=20 d.       admission tickets to the scenic spots=20  =20  Application Deadline: March 12, 2010 (first come first serve)   Eligibility:  1.        CUNY undergraduate and graduate=20 2.        Students from any other colleges in the U.S.; and=20 3.        CUNY faculty, staff and alumni=20   STOCS scholarships and financial Aid are available for qualified students.  =20 For more information about the program,=20  1. subject: U.S. Census is Hiring!
message: Looking for a way to earn extra income and make a difference?  AT THE CENSUS BUREAU, YOU CAN DO BOTH.  The U.S. Census Bureau needs to hire local residents for a variety of temporary, part-time jobs. Most of the jobs will be in the field and will require you to conduct household interviews. The information you collect is confidential and will be used to help determine Congressional representation and the allocation of more than $400 billion in federal funds to improve communities across America.  Available positions:  - Crew Leaders  - Field Staff (Enumerators)  - Office Clerks  - $13.50-$20.25 per hour  - Part-time/Temporary  - Paid training  - Close to home  - Evening and weekend work  - Flexible hours to fit your school schedule   Qualifications:  - Must be 18 years of age or older  - U.S. citizens given preference,  but everyone encouraged to apply.  Work authorization a must.  - Valid social security number  - Must pass a required written test    Call 1-866-861-2010 to schedule a test today!   The U.S. Census Bureau is an Equal Opportunity Employer.  http://www.2010censusjobs.gov  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

from_: "Jennifer S. Rubain, Director of Diversity and Equity Programs" <jrubain@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Last chance to take diversity survey and win prizes!
message: The Diversity and Inclusion Plan Implementation Committee is evaluating the college's efforts to create a diverse and inclusive environment.  Unless otherwise specified, diversity is broadly defined as a range of differences among people in terms of age, ethnicity, family background, gender, language, learning styles, level of academic preparedness, national origin, physical or mental abilities, race, religion, sexual orientation, and socioeconomic status.       Keeping this definition in mind, we ask that you complete the survey below, which assesses attitudes and experiences related to diversity issues on campus.  This survey is completely anonymous and participation is voluntary!  You may choose to answer all, some, or none of the questions.   We hope, however, that you will choose to fully participate because your input is valuable and helps us assess the current campus climate and plan future initiatives.  Participants may enter a RAFFLE once the survey is completed for a chance to win a Kindle Wireless Reading Device, $200 gift card, BC parking pass, BC gym membership, and many smaller prizes!  Raffle winners will be notified on March 1, 2010.    If you have questions about this survey, please contact Jennifer Rubain, director of diversity and equity programs, at jrubain@brooklyn.cuny.edu or 718.951.4128.     We will present the results of the survey in a Town Hall meeting this semester.   To begin the survey, click below and enter the username guest:  https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/diversity/students   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject:
Memorial Service for Distinguished Professor Emeritus Hans
 Trefousse Set for March 11
message: The Department of History mourns the loss of its long-time colleague Hans Trefousse.  A memorial will be held on Thursday, March 11, at 2:30 p.m. in Tanger Auditorium of the Brooklyn College Library.  Friends, former colleagues, and the public are invited to attend.  Born in Frankfurt, Germany, in 1921, Professor Trefousse graduated from City College of New York in 1942, and received his Ph.D. from Columbia University in 1950.  During the Second World War, he served as Captain in U.S. Army Intelligence.  After teaching part-time in the School of General Studies beginning in 1946, he rose in the ranks from Instructor to Distinguished Professor in a career at Brooklyn College that lasted half a century (1950-1999).  He was still teaching at the college's Institute for Retirees in Pursuit of Education in fall 2009.  Recipient of the Brooklyn College Distinguished Teacher Award, a John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Fellowship, and a grant from the American Council of Learned Societies, Professor Trefousse was a specialist in the history of the American Civil War and Reconstruction.  He published widely and right up to the end of his life.  Among his many major works are studies of reconstruction and radical republicanism and biographies of Andrew Johnson, Rutherford B. Hayes, Carl Schurz, and Thaddeus Stevens.   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

 Job and Internship Fair

Here's what you can do to prepare yourself for the job search:=20  1. Make sure you are registered with the Magner Center for Career Development and Internships to receive information about job opportunities and utilize our services. Register via the career tab of the portal.  2. Take advantage of the following services and events specifically designed to help you with the upcoming Job and Internship Fair on March 12. You can register for all these events via the career tab of the portal: http://portal.brooklyn.edu.  =20 TARGET R=C9SUM=C9 REVIEW DAY Friday, March 5 11 a.m.-2:30 p.m. 1303 James Hall=20  A Target representative will be available for walk-in r=E9sum=E9 review for students. subject: Open House: Study Abroad in China
message: Place:  3439 Boylan Hall, Brooklyn College   Come and learn about an inexpensive way to travel and study in China:=20  See the new Beijing and the new China after the Olympics  Enjoy Shanghai World Expo 2010 (May to October 2010)   Summer Study Abroad in China, Tentative Dates: May 27-June 23, 2010   Application Deadline (now extended to): March 22, 2010 (first come first serve)   One-Month Program to Five Famous Chinese Cities:  Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou & Shanghai  With side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain, Tibet  Check the program's website (photos, comments, FAQ's, etc. ) for details at:=20  http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china/  =20 Students may choose 3-6 credits of study from the following:  1. History 53: Revolutionary China=20  2. Core 20.06: Development of the Silk Road  3. Business 76.5: Asian Business=20  4. Chinese 1.1: Beginners Chinese; Chinese 2.1: Intermediate Chinese=20  5. Speech 18.5: Intercultural Communication=20  6. Speech 23: Business & Professional Communication (cross-cultural perspectives)=20  7. CC1.1 Classical Cultures (China)  =20  Program Features:  - All courses are taught by Brooklyn College faculty, for CUNY-BC credit=20  - Group travel to 5 most famous and beautiful Chinese cities: Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou & Shanghai=20  - Field trips to sites of historical and cultural importance (e.g., TianAnMen Square, the Great Wall, Forbidden City, Summer Palace, Terra Cotta Warriors, Ancient City Walls, Buddhist Temples, Jewish Synagogue, Great Islamic Mosques, Suzhou Gardens, Silk Factory, Cloisonn=E9 Factory, the Bund, etc)=20  - Experience Chinese culture, interact with local people, have a real feel of Chinese life=20  - Travel and sightseeing are arranged by professional travel agencies=20  - Side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain or Tibet=20 =20  Enjoy the beautiful Shanghai as host of World Expo 2010 (May to October 2010) . For a quick look at the Shanghai Expo "City Rhapsody: The Site of Expo Shanghai," please go to this link:  http://en.expo2010.cn/sr/video/shipin2.htm=20  =20  Total Estimated Program Cost: only $2,898, which includes:  a. round-trip international tickets (NYC to Beijing; Shanghai to NYC)=20  b. transportation within and between the Chinese cities=20  c. nice hotels in all the cities in China=20  d. admission tickets to the scenic spots=20   Eligibility:  1. CUNY undergraduate and graduate=20  2. Students from any other colleges in the U.S.; and=20  3. CUNY faculty, staff and alumni=20   STOCS scholarships and financial Aid are available for qualified students.  =20 For more information about the program,=20  1. Visit the program website: http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china  2. E-mail Professor Lu at CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu , or  3. Call 718-951-5225 (ask for Ms. Sonia Garrick)  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210.  through March 17
message: Dear Faculty, Staff, Students, and Other Members of the Brooklyn College Community,=20  As you may recall, last year's food drive-done in collaboration with Assemblywoman Rhoda Jacobs of the 42nd District-was wildly successful. =20  The needs of local food pantries have not diminished; in fact, they have increased significantly since last year.  In response, we will conduct another food drive this year. Join us for:  The Brooklyn College Annual Food Drive Wednesday, March 10-Wednesday, March 17  Here is how you can participate:  =B7         Locate one of the many designated "Food Drive" cartons or boxes designed for Food Drive donations (most of them residing in the main offices of academic departments and administrative offices/centers).=20  =B7        Contribute, and encourage your friends and colleagues to contribute any of the following non-perishable items (food pantries cannot accept perishable items):  baby formula                 =20 baby food                        =20 canned vegetables canned fruit     =20 canned or packaged fish/meats evaporated milk dry pasta rice      =20  =B7       If you would like to volunteer, please call Bonnie Impagliazzo or Milena Danyo at ext. 5391. subject: Robert L. Hess Scholar-in-Residence Visit with Dr. Eleanor Sterling
message: The Ethyle R. Wolfe Institute for the Humanities, in cooperation with the Robert L. Hess Scholar-in-Residence Planning Committee, presents:  Robert L. Hess Scholar-in-Residence Eleanor J. Sterling  Monday, March 8 3:40-4:55 p.m. Sustainability and Community Health Gold Room, Student Center  Tuesday, March 9 11 a.m.-12:15 p.m. Human Development and Its Impact on Diversity Alumni Lounge, Student Center  3-4:30 p.m. Coffee Talk: The Carbon Footprint of Coffee The Wolfe Institute, 2231 Boylan Hall  Wednesday, March 10 5:30-6:30 p.m. The Robert L. Hess Memorial Lecture You Don't Know What You've Got 'Til It's Gone: Sustaining Biological, Linguistic and Cultural Diversity Woody Tanger Auditorium, Brooklyn College Library  Thursday, March 11 4-5:45 p.m. BioBlitz Information Session Foyer, Ingersoll Hall Extension  Friday, March 12 12:30-1:15 p.m. Biology Seminar on the Palmyra Atoll 113 Ingersoll Hall Extension  Eleanor J. Sterling is the director of the American Museum of Natural History Center for Biodiversity and Conservation (CBC), where she oversees all aspects of the center's operations. She is also director of graduate studies for the Department of Ecology, Evolution, and Environmental Biology at Columbia University. Among her books are Vietnam: A Natural History, co-authored with colleagues at the CBC; Remote Sensing for Ecology and Conservation, edited with CBC colleagues and J. Robinson, W. Turner and S. Spector; and Problem Solving in Conservation Biology and Wildlife Management: Exercises for Class, Field, and Laboratory, edited with J.P. Gibbs.   For information, contact the Wolfe Institute at 718.951.5847 or wolfeinstitute@brooklyn.cuny.edu.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Financial Aid Information 2010
message: This E-Alert message is being sent to all undergraduate and graduate students currently eligible to register for the summer or fall 2010 term at Brooklyn College.  Its intent is to alert those students who are applying for financial aid for these upcoming terms regarding the May 1, 2010 filing date.  Please note that your 2010-2011 FAFSA must be filed by May 1, 2010 in order for your aid to be appropriately applied by the payment deadlines for the upcoming semesters (summer and/or fall 2010). If you do not file your FAFSA by this date, your aid will still be processed for the year but you will risk not having it available at the time term payment is due. In that case, you will be responsible for your bill until your aid is processed. Failure to make payment arrangements could result in a bar on your record and possible cancellation of your classes. Please refer to the 2010 Continuing Student Registration and Payment Schedule listed in the Schedule of Classes to determine your due date.  Please note:  * Don't Delay! Do it today!  * Processed financial aid is how you protect your classes from being dropped   * Late applicants seriously run the risk of not being able to secure their classes, receive book check, vouchers, or receiving timely refunds  If you have filed your FAFSA...Thanks!  The Office of Financial Aid has begun processing applications for next year and you will be hearing from us very soon.   If you have not filed your FAFSA yet please do so now!     NOTE: All students receiving Vallone, CUNY Honors, and various other scholarships must also file the FAFSA every year.   For specific details on how to start the 2010-2011 financial aid application process go to the financial aid page of the web portal for Brooklyn College at http://finaid.brooklyn.cuny.edu and begin.  You may also go directly to the federal webpage at www.fafsa.ed.gov and file a renewal FAFSA or initial FAFSA application.  If you have any questions please feel free to email us at finaid@brooklyn.cuny.edu    ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/eAlerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

from_: "Peter L. Pampalone, First Year Specialist, CAASS" <PeterP@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Brooklyn College: First Year Academic Advisor Greeting
message: My name is Peter Pampalone, and I am the First Year Specialist for The Center for Academic Advisement and Student Success (CAASS). I hope your semester is going well so far. We most likely met at registration.  I just wanted to send out a quick greeting welcoming you to Brooklyn College and inviting you to come see me, so you can receive some one-on-one advisement regarding college-wide requirements, first year strategies, or any other issues you would like addressed.    I am available for appointments Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays from 9:30am to 4:30pm. On Tuesdays and Thursdays I am also available from 9:30am to 4: 30pm; these days are the Center's walk-in days, so no appointment is necessary. If you want to see me specifically, you may e-mail me at peterp@brooklyn.cuny.edu and let me know you are going to be dropping by to see me. The coming weeks in March have historically been lighter in terms of student volume. This means that it would be in your best interest to schedule some time to come and meet with me because I will have greater availability, thus there will be more open appointment slots for you to choose from.   Also, I am more than happy to answer any question through e-mail.  Send me your questions or concerns, and if it turns out that I cannot handle your issue just through an e-mail, we can arrange a meeting.   To make an appointment, please do the following:    - Log on to the BC portal  - Click the Advisement tab  - Scroll under the Academic Advisement bar  - Click the Schedule an Advisement Appointment button  - Follow prompts to make an appointment.    I look forward to meeting with you to clarify anything that is unclear and to ensure that the transition to Brooklyn College is as smooth a process as possible. Please feel free to get in touch with me.   Be on the lookout for an e-mail regarding special workshops geared for freshmen students preparing to take the English 1 Exit Exam--coming soon!     Regards,  Peter L. Pampalone First Year Specialist CAASS 3207 Boylan Hall 718-951-5471
