subject: Fall 2010 Financial Aid Information
message: Fall 2010 Financial Aid Information   The e-alert is being sent to all degree-seeking graduate and undergraduate students at Brooklyn College.  If you intend to use financial aid to cover any portion of your fall 2010 tuition and fees, please read the following "Top 5 Recommendations" designed to provide you with the best possible service and assist you in avoiding unnecessary delays in processing.  TOP 5 Recommendations  1. Register for your classes as soon as possible.  In order for your financial aid to properly displayed on your account you need to be registered. Additionally, this makes the processing of your awards much smoother since it can be determined if you are full or part-time.  2. File a 2010-2011 FAFSA and complete the financial aid process.  If your Student Aid Reports indicate that additional information needs to be submitted to the financial aid office, please do so immediately.  Documentation and loan applications can be faxed to (718) 951-4778 or mailed to the financial aid office, or submitted at the Enrollment Services Center.  3. Submit your direct loan application now.  Applications are available on our website.  Do not wait until August to submit loan applications. It will seriously hinder your ability to secure registration and to receive funds for books, etc.  4. Graduate Students are especially urged to complete the loan application and the Rights and Responsibilities document process now.  Do not wait until the start of the semester to begin.  5. Sign up for the CUNY Scholar Support Card, or the Direct Deposit program. These are the fastest and easiest ways to access your financial aid funds.  This will allow electronic deposits of all refunds to your account.  Specifics about each can be found in the July issue of the "Financial Aid Flash" at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/pub/1401.htm  on the Brooklyn College financial aid web page.  If you have any questions, please feel free to email us at finaid@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or stop by the Enrollment Services Center and speak with a financial aid representative.  (Please do not respond directly to this email.  Replies to this message are routed to an unmonitored mailbox.)  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: CLAS Student Activity Fee Increase
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Effective the fall 2010 semester, the CLAS Student Activity Fee is $112.05. This constitutes a $1.50 increase that has been approved by the student body. This fee will be earmarked and allocated by the Brooklyn College Association to the recently formed Study Abroad Scholarship Association (SASA) to provide funding for currently enrolled Brooklyn College CLAS students who are in good standing and meet the College's established procedure for scholarships to study abroad.   If you have already paid your fall 2010 bill, please make arrangements to pay the remaining balance.    You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). You may also make full payment online using an electronic funds transfer (e-check) at no cost, or a credit card through WebCentral. VISA cards are not accepted. There is a 2.65% convenience fee associated with the use of all credit or debit cards.     You can access a list of payment options at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay. For further information, please call 718-951-5200, e-mail us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad Center.    The Enrollment Services Center will be open the following regular hours*:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. - 10 p.m. Friday - Sunday:          9 a.m. -  5 p.m.  *Please note that the Enrollment Services Center will be closed on the following days: July 16, July 23, July 30, August 6, and August 13.  For phone assistance, please contact the Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services during the following hours:   Monday - Thursday        9 a.m. -  7:45 p.m.  Friday                   9 a.m. - 4:45 p.m.   Thank you. If you do not plan on attending this fall, please make sure to drop your courses before August 26 to avoid liability charges. Please see below for the fall 2010 liability schedule:  100% Refund: Drop prior to August 26 75% Refund: Drop August 26 - September 1 50% Refund: Drop September 2 - September 8 25% Refund: Drop September 9 - September 15 0% Refund: Withdraw September 16 and thereafter  You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). subject: Fall 2010 Payment Reminder
message: Thank you for registering for the fall 2010 semester. Your tuition payment is due on July 29th. According to our records, your account reflects an outstanding balance. Please make arrangements to settle your bill by the bill due date. Failure to do so may result in the cancellation of your courses. Please note that a partial financial aid award does not constitute full payment and will not secure your classes. You are responsible for any balance that remains after financial aid is applied to your bill. If you do not plan on attending this fall, please make sure to drop your courses before August 26 to avoid liability charges. Please see below for the fall 2010 liability schedule:  100% Refund: Drop prior to August 26 75% Refund: Drop August 26 - September 1 50% Refund: Drop September 2 - September 8 25% Refund: Drop September 9 - September 15 0% Refund: Withdraw September 16 and thereafter  You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). You may also make full payment online using an electronic funds transfer (e-check) at no cost, or a credit card through WebCentral. VISA cards are not accepted. There is a 2.65% convenience fee associated with the use of all credit or debit cards.     You can access a list of payment options at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay. For further information, please call 718-951-5200, e-mail us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad Center. If you feel that you have received this e-mail in error, please feel free to e-mail or contact us over the phone.    The Enrollment Services Center will be open the following regular hours*:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. - 10 p.m. Friday - Sunday:          9 a.m. -  5 p.m.  *Please note that the Enrollment Services Center will be closed on the following days: July 16, July 23, July 30, August 6, and August 13.  For phone assistance, please contact the Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services during the following hours:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. -  7:45 p.m.  Friday:                   9 a.m. - 4:45 p.m.   Thank you.    The Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services

subject: Fall 2010 Payment Reminder
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Thank you for registering for the fall 2010 semester. Your tuition payment is due on July 29th. According to our records, your account reflects an outstanding balance. Please make arrangements to settle your bill by the bill due date. Failure to do so may result in the cancellation of your courses. Please note that a partial financial aid award does not constitute full payment and will not secure your classes. You are responsible for any balance that remains after financial aid is applied to your bill. If you do not plan on attending this fall, please make sure to drop your courses before August 26 to avoid liability charges. Please see below for the fall 2010 liability schedule:  100% Refund: Drop prior to August 26 75% Refund: Drop August 26 - September 1 50% Refund: Drop September 2 - September 8 25% Refund: Drop September 9 - September 15 0% Refund: Withdraw September 16 and thereafter  You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). You may also make full payment online using an electronic funds transfer (e-check) at no cost, or a credit card through WebCentral. VISA cards are not accepted. There is a 2.65% convenience fee associated with the use of all credit or debit cards.     You can access a list of payment options at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay. For further information, please call 718-951-5200, e-mail us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad Center. If you feel that you have received this e-mail in error, please feel free to e-mail or contact us over the phone.    The Enrollment Services Center will be open the following regular hours*:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. - 10 p.m. Friday - Sunday:          9 a.m. -  5 p.m.  *Please note that the Enrollment Services Center will be closed on the following days: July 30, August 6, and August 13.  For phone assistance, please contact the Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services during the following hours*:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. -  7:45 p.m.  Friday:                   9 a.m. - 4:45 p.m.  *Please note that the Office of the Bursar will be closed on the following days: July 30, August 6, and August 13.   Thank you.    The Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services   		This email was sent to: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN <jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com>

Click "Your Account" at the top of any Amazon.com page, then click "Your Seller Account" on the right side of the page, under "Your Other Accounts."  2. See instructions below.  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  AFTER YOU SHIP THE ORDER, CONFIRM THE SHIPMENT  You can confirm shipments easily in Manage Orders:  1. In your Seller Account, under the "Manage Your Orders" heading, click "View your orders" to find the order you want to confirm.  2. Click the "Confirm shipment" button next to the order (or below the order if you are looking at an Order Details page).   3. Select the Ship Date and Carrier (such as USPS) from the drop-down lists.  4. Enter the Shipping Service (such as Ground) and the Tracking ID, if any (supplied by the carrier).  5. Click the "Confirm shipment" button.   For information on confirming shipment of multiple orders at once, search on "confirm ship" in seller Help.   - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  HOW TO CANCEL ORDERS   Sellers should have sufficient inventory on hand to fulfill all orders on time. However, in those rare cases when ordered items are not available, please cancel the order promptly. After you cancel the order, Amazon will send the buyer an order cancellation e-mail.  You can cancel orders easily in Manage Orders:  1. In your Seller Account under the "Manage Your Orders" heading, click "View your orders" to find the order you want to cancel.  2. Click the "Cancel order" button next to the order (or below the order if you are looking at an Order Details page).  3. Select the appropriate reason, and then click Submit.  For information on cancelling orders using a feed, search on "cancel multiple orders" in seller Help.   Note that if you have already confirmed shipment of the order, you will no longer be able to cancel it. In that case, you would issue a refund and work with the buyer to arrange a return. For information about refunds, search on "refund orders" in seller Help.  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  ABOUT YOUR PAYMENT  This transaction will be posted to your Marketplace Payments account after you confirm shipment. Funds in your Marketplace Payments account are automatically disbursed to your bank account every 14 days. After funds are disbursed from your Marketplace Payments account, it can take up to 5 business days for your bank to make the funds available in your checking account.  Please make sure your bank account information is always up to date so there are no delays in disbursements to your bank account. To do so:  1. Go to your Seller Account and click the "Seller Account Information" link in the Settings section.   2. In the Bank Account section, click the Add or Edit button to update your checking account information.

subject: Today
message: I would appreciate if you would do the following as early as possible so they get done and not forgotten about:  1 - Bathrooms - please make sure all three bathrooms have the following, do this after Estella cleans each bathroom: 	* Regular Toilet Paper 	* Torn Toilet Paper 	* At least 1 full wet ones, preferably 2 	* A clean hand towel 	* A full liquid Soap, there is refill under the sink in the upstairs & basement bathrooms and new ones in the Simcha closet  2 - Leah Salad dressing - double recipe in 2 different containers, 1 for us and 1 to send to Webers for Shabbas Shevah Brachos - Shelah Shudis

subject: Brooklyn College Navigators
message: The BC Navigators of the Office of Admissions are inviting all students to take advantage of an exciting job opportunity on campus. BC Navigators are ambassadors of Brooklyn College's Office of Admissions, leaders on campus and role models to their peers.  We are looking for the best of the best to join our dynamic and ever-growing team. Do you have what it takes to be a BC Navigator? *  A vibrant personality *  School spirit *  Knowledge about the campus *  Experiences you would like to share with others  If you answered yes to any of these questions, we want you! Become part of the team and see what being a Navigator is all about.  For more information or to be considered, please send your resume and a cover letter to bcnavigators@brooklyn.cuny.edu.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Online Services Interruption Sunday 7/25
message: Please be advised that this Sunday, July 25, from 10 a.m. extending throughout the day and evening, ITS will be upgrading the infrastructure and software that supports many of the College's online services and tools. During this time, the BC WebCentral portal, faculty profiles, department/program/course views and other tools will be intermittently unavailable. We will try to minimize the interruptions to each service and apologize for the inconvenience.   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Save Time! Students Services Now Online
message: Did you know that many of the services offered at the Enrollment Services Center are also available online via BC WebCentral? Brooklyn College has a user-friendly portal that allows you to do many transactions from any computer with internet access. You can register online, check your registration appointment date, obtain an enrollment certification letter, order a transcript, pay your tuition, and view your billing and financial aid information.  You can also schedule an appointment to see a specialist in the Offices of the Registrar, Financial Aid, and the Center for Academic Advisement and Student Success. Log-in to BC WebCentral, click on the links under the "eServices" tab, and check out the services available to you.  The Enrollment Services Center, located in the lobby of the West Quad Center, offers registration, financial aid, ID, cashiering, and check distribution services to the Brooklyn College community.  Our regular hours of operation are as follows*: Monday - Thursday: 9:00 am - 10:00 pm Friday - Sunday: 9:00 am - 5:00 pm  Cashiering services end 15 minutes prior to the Center's closing.  *We will be closed on Friday, August 13th.   Please note: Registration services will be moved to the Computer Lab located in the West End Building (WEB) from August 16th to September 3rd.   Sincerely,  The Enrollment Services Center Team. (718) 758-8150   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Fall 2010 Payment Reminder
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Thank you for registering for the fall 2010 semester. Your tuition payment is now due. According to our records, your account reflects an outstanding balance. Please make arrangements to settle your bill. Failure to do so may result in the cancellation of your courses. Please note that a partial financial aid award does not constitute full payment and will not secure your classes. You are responsible for any balance that remains after financial aid is applied to your bill. If you do not plan on attending this fall, please make sure to drop your courses before August 26 to avoid liability charges. Please see below for the fall 2010 liability schedule:  100% Refund: Drop prior to August 26 75% Refund: Drop August 26 - September 1 50% Refund: Drop September 2 - September 8 25% Refund: Drop September 9 - September 15 0% Refund: Withdraw September 16 and thereafter  You can view a copy of your bill by logging onto your WebSIMS account via the BC WebCentral Portal (http://portal.brooklyn.edu). You may also make full payment online using an electronic funds transfer (e-check) at no cost, or a credit card through WebCentral. VISA cards are not accepted. There is a 2.65% convenience fee associated with the use of all credit or debit cards. Please note that CUNY/CIS will be conducting Solaris system maintenance this Thursday, August 19th, from 5:30 pm to 7:30 pm. During this maintenance, the EDS credit card payment will be unavailable.     You can access a list of payment options at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/billpay. For further information, please call 718-951-5200, e-mail us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad Center. If you feel that you have received this e-mail in error, please feel free to e-mail or contact us over the phone.    The Enrollment Services Center will be open the following regular hours:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. - 10 p.m. Friday - Sunday:          9 a.m. -  5 p.m.   For phone assistance, please contact the Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services during the following hours:   Monday - Thursday:        9 a.m. - 7:45 p.m.  Friday:                   9 a.m. - 4:45 p.m.   Thank you.    The Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services  		This email was sent to: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN <jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com>

from_: "Milga Morales, Vice President for Student Affairs" <studentaffairs@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Brooklyn College Entering Student Orientation
message: Reminder!  Members of the College community are invited to greet new students at the New Student Orientation Campus Experience on Tuesday, August 24, 9:30 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.**  The day promises to be filled with excitement and festivities on both the Central and West quads. Music will be provided by the Brooklyn College radio station, while various clubs and organizations will be presenting and recruiting at the Club Fair. There will also be games and entertainment as well as a chance to meet both student government leaders and the cheerleaders, athletes and coaches from our championship teams. Come out and let's give our new students a campus experience to remember.  **The Convocation originally scheduled for August 31 at noon has been restructured and is now an integral part of the Campus Experience event.  Below are some of the day's activities. For the full program, visit http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/pub/sa/.  Club Fair Maui Wowi Smoothies Greek "Stroll Off" Free Coca-Cola Samples Soap Box Debate Face Painting Caricatures Photos with the New School Mascot Calligraphy Hula for Health Hula Hoop Contest Pull for Peace (Tug-of-war) Music on the Quads Veterans Display Double Dutch Division of Student Affairs Poster Display   Volunteers are welcome!  For more information, reply to studentaffairs@brooklyn.cuny.edu.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Enroll now in the CUNY Scholar Support Card
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Enroll now for CUNY's Scholar Support Prepaid Card! This is a fast, secure, and convenient way for you to receive your financial aid refunds. Enrolling in this program ensures quick access to funds once disbursed and you no longer will have to wait for a check in the mail.  To receive your financial aid on the prepaid card you have to enroll by following these easy steps:  1. Visit www.enroll.citiprepaid.com/CUNY 2. Enter your information to verify your identity 3. Opt in for the Prepaid Card 4. Verify your mailing address    Please be advised that you can only apply for the CUNY Scholar Support Card if you are eligible for financial aid. This is not a credit card; it is a prepaid MasterCard card accepted at any store or ATM where MasterCard is accepted. Availability of funds depends on the type of aid as well as the payment distribution date. Receiving financial aid payments via check or direct deposit is still an option.  If you need further information, please call Citibank customer support services at (866)326-8689.    Thank you. You may use any of the deposit options in the PokerStars Cashier to repay any funds still owing, including the eCheck option.  Transfers received from other players will also be applied towards any negative balance you have as well.    We apologize for the inconveniences this may have caused you.  If you have any questions, please email us at "PokerStars Support" <support@pokerstars.com>  Regards,  PokerStars Payments Department

from_: BC in China Study Abroad Program <CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Open House for CUNY-BC Winter 2010-11 in China Program
message: Join us for an open house for the Winter 2010-11 Study Abroad in China Program on any of the following dates:  Tuesday, August 31, 12:30-1:30 p.m. Wednesday, September 1, 12:30-1:30 p.m. Tuesday, September 7, 12:30-1:30 p.m.  Location: 3439 Boylan Hall   Winter 2010-11 Study Abroad in China=20 Tentative Trip Dates: December 29, 2010-January 23, 2011  This four-week program is an inexpensive way to travel and study in China, during which students visit five of the most famous Chinese cities (Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou and Shanghai) and take side trips to Hong Kong, Tibet, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii) or Yellow Mountain.  For details (photos, comments, FAQs, etc.), visit the program's website at:=20 http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china/   Students may choose 3 to 6 credits of study from the following: 1. History 3534: Revolutionary China=20 2. Core 3206: Development of the Silk Road 3. Business 3175: Asian Business=20 4. Chinese 1010: Beginners Chinese, and Chinese 1020: Intermediate Chinese=20 5. Speech 1619: Intercultural Communication=20 6. Speech 2623: Business & Professional Communication (cross-cultural perspectives)=20 7. Core 1010: Classical Cultures (China)   Program features: * All courses are taught by Brooklyn College faculty, for CUNY-BC credit. * Group travel to five of the most famous and beautiful Chinese cities: Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou and Shanghai. * Field trips to sites of historical and cultural importance (e.g., Tiananmen Square, the Great Wall, Forbidden City, Summer Palace, Terra Cotta Warriors, ancient city walls, Buddhist temples, Jewish synagogue, Islamic mosques, Suzhou Gardens, silk factory, Cloisonn=E9 factory, the Bund, Shanghai Pudong Financial District and China's Wall Street, etc.). * Experience Chinese culture, interact with local people, get a real feel of Chinese life. * Travel and sightseeing are arranged by professional travel agencies. * Side trips to Hong Kong, Tibet, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii) or Yellow Mountain  =20 Total estimated program cost: only $2,898, which includes: * Round-trip international tickets (New York to Beijing; Shanghai to New York)=20 * Transportation within and between Chinese cities=20 * Nice hotels in all cities=20 * Admission tickets to scenic spots=20   Eligibility: 1. CUNY undergraduate and graduate students, or=20 2. Students from any other colleges in the United States  STOCS scholarships and financial aid are available for qualified students.  Application deadline: October 15, 2010 (first come, first served)   For more information about the program:=20 * Visit the program website: http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china. * E-mail Professor Lu at CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu. * Call 718.951.5225 (ask for Sonia Garrick).  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: VERY IMPORTANT: Internet Explorer 8 Issues on Blackboard
message: The Blackboard upgrade has introduced an unexpected problem with Internet Explorer 8.  When logging into the CUNY Portal and/or Blackboard using IE 8, you will receive a dialogue box asking whether you "want to view only the web content that was delivered securely." You must select NO to allow External Links to open within Blackboard (for an example, see http://bit.ly/c2Yzi5). Otherwise, External Links in your course configured to launch within Blackboard will fail to open. You may also configure External Links in Blackboard to open in a new window.  Alternatively, you may also enable IE 8 to simultaneously access secure and unsecure, or mixed, content with the following steps:  1. Go to Tools, Internet Options. 2. Select the "Security" Tab and then click on the "Custom Level" button. 3. Scroll down until you see the option: "Display mixed content." Select "Enable." 4. Click OK. Then you will get a "Security Warning" pop-up. Click Yes.  For a demonstration, visit http://bit.ly/9HbXn4.  The problem is limited to Internet Explorer 8 and does not occur when using Firefox.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

Although this grade does not carry an academic penalty, it does carry a financial liability. In other words, if you register for classes and receive WN grades, you are responsible for 100% of the tuition for those courses.   Therefore it is very important that you inform the College by September 8, 2010 if you do not intend to attend classes this semester. subject: Gain a Competitive Edge in Your Career Search
message: Dear Student,  The Magner Center for Career Development and Internships is offering a superb series of Professional Skills Training Workshops this semester. Attendees will learn job skills demanded by employers of prospective employees. Register now. Seats are limited.  Sign up for all workshops by logging onto BC WebCentral, http://portal.brooklyn.cuny.edu, and select the Career Tab.  For each event we will give away a free book on the topic to the first 20 preregistered students who attend.   Working It: How to Succeed as a Woman in a Professional Workforce   Guest Speaker: Marisol Gonzalez, HBO Producer/Filmmaker Thursday, October 7, 12:30-2 p.m. Women's Center, 227 Ingersoll Hall Extension  Gain valuable insights about career success from a highly successful and accomplished professional. This event is a must for all women hoping to make it! CoSponsored with the Women's Center.    Skills for Surviving Your Turbulent Twenties Guest Speaker: Marcos Salazar, Author and Entrepreneur      Tuesday, October 19, 12:15-2:15 p.m. Jefferson Williams Lounge, Student Center  Author and entrepreneur Marcos Salazar will discuss the personal and career trials and tribulations we all face in our twenties. He'll share his insights as to how you can successfully transition and thrive during your most turbulent young adult years.    Freelancers' Career Forum Guest Speakers:  TBA   Tuesday, October 26, 12:15-2:15 p.m. Penthouse, Student Center  Tired of clocking in and losing out? Want to pursue creative, fulfilling work on your own time and also make a living in the process? Panelists from several freelance fields will offer tips, advice, how-to's and everything you will need to pursue a freelance career.    Land Your First Job and Build Your Professional Network  Guest Speakers:  Al Tretola and Anthony Fasano  Tuesday, November 2, 12:15-2:15 p.m. Gold Room, Student Center  Are you doing all the right things in your job search? Seasoned recruiter Al Tretola and career coach Anthony Fasano will provide competitive tips for:  Understanding Yourself and Knowing How to Market Yourself, Resume Presentation/Writing Techniques, Interviewing/Negotiating Techniques and Seven Steps to Building Successful LinkedIn Relationships.    Networking With Others to Succeed Guest Speaker: Barbara V. Pimentel, Corporate Communications Office, Mitsubishi International Corporation Friday, November 12, 10:30 a.m.-11:30 a.m. Alumni Lounge, Student Center  Being connected to the right people increases your chances for success in the job search and in your career. This workshop will help you identify who is in your network (yes, you have a network), how to network effectively and how not using your network will negatively affect you.   Secrets of the Successful Entrepreneur  Guest Speaker:  TBA   Tuesday, November 16, 12:15-2:15 p.m. Jefferson Williams Lounge, Student Center  Want to make your own job? Be your own boss? Learn from several successful entrepreneurs as they describe how they were able to form new ventures and see them through to success.    **The Willard and Eleanor Archie Professional Skills Training Program at Brooklyn College is designed to prepare students for the competition they will face in their careers. Students will develop the skills and attitudes most often cited by employers as leading to career mobility and productivity: communication, teamwork, leadership, critical thinking, working in a diverse environment, etc. These workshops/panels are facilitated by professionals, alumni and experts in the field. Refreshments will be provided.   Michael Sarrao Professional Skills Training Coordinator  The Willard and Eleanor Archie Professional Skills Training Program Magner Center for Career Development and Internships  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

Condition: Used - Very Good Listing ID: 0905GD8WYE2 SKU: 8H-7U0V-AS9R Quantity: 1 Order date: 09/08/2010 Buyer's price: $18.50 Amazon commission: -$5.12 Shipping credit: $3.99 Your earnings: $17.37  You have agreed to ship no later than two business days after the order date of 09/08/2010. Keep in mind that you are responsible for the item until it reaches the buyer at the address provided within your Amazon.com account.  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  SHIPPING INFORMATION FOR THIS ORDER  You can see the order details, print an address label and packing slip, and confirm shipment of the order in the "Manage Your Orders" section of your Seller Account:  1. Click "Your Account" at the top of any Amazon.com page, then click "Your Seller Account" on the right side of the page, under "Your Other Accounts."  2. Within the Manage Your Orders section, click "View Your Orders" and find order ID 102-0201472-0797077.   3. Click the Order ID link to display the Order Details page. You will see the shipping address, the shipping speed, and a "Contact Buyer" link. You can print an address label and packing slip.  4. After you ship the order, be sure to confirm the shipment. We will then charge the buyer, credit your Marketplace Payments account, and notify the buyer that the order has been shipped. See instructions below.  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  AFTER YOU SHIP THE ORDER, CONFIRM THE SHIPMENT  You can confirm shipments easily in Manage Orders:  1. In your Seller Account, under the "Manage Your Orders" heading, click "View your orders" to find the order you want to confirm.  2. Click the "Confirm shipment" button next to the order (or below the order if you are looking at an Order Details page).   3. Select the Ship Date and Carrier (such as USPS) from the drop-down lists.  4. Enter the Shipping Service (such as Ground) and the Tracking ID, if any (supplied by the carrier).  5. Click the "Confirm shipment" button.   For information on confirming shipment of multiple orders at once, search on "confirm ship" in seller Help.   - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  HOW TO CANCEL ORDERS   Sellers should have sufficient inventory on hand to fulfill all orders on time. However, in those rare cases when ordered items are not available, please cancel the order promptly. After you cancel the order, Amazon will send the buyer an order cancellation e-mail.  You can cancel orders easily in Manage Orders:  1. In your Seller Account under the "Manage Your Orders" heading, click "View your orders" to find the order you want to cancel.  2. Click the "Cancel order" button next to the order (or below the order if you are looking at an Order Details page).  3. Select the appropriate reason, and then click Submit.  For information on cancelling orders using a feed, search on "cancel multiple orders" in seller Help.   Note that if you have already confirmed shipment of the order, you will no longer be able to cancel it. In that case, you would issue a refund and work with the buyer to arrange a return. For information about refunds, search on "refund orders" in seller Help.  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  ABOUT YOUR PAYMENT  This transaction will be posted to your Marketplace Payments account after you confirm shipment. Funds in your Marketplace Payments account are automatically disbursed to your bank account every 14 days. After funds are disbursed from your Marketplace Payments account, it can take up to 5 business days for your bank to make the funds available in your checking account.  Please make sure your bank account information is always up to date so there are no delays in disbursements to your bank account. To do so:  1. Go to your Seller Account and click the "Seller Account Information" link in the Settings section.   2. In the Bank Account section, click the Add or Edit button to update your checking account information.

subject: Get Connected With Alumni Professionals in Your Career Field
message: The Magner Center for Career Development and Internships has created a new workshop: Building Professional Relationships: Mentors and Networking.  Networking and acquiring mentors have become two essential ingredients to career success. It is at least partially true that "it's not what you know, it's who you know."  Attending the workshop will teach you how to establish professional networks and, most importantly, how to get an alumni mentor through the Magner Center. Coming to the workshop qualifies you to join the Magner Alumni & Student Professional Networking Group on Linkedin that connects you with hundreds of BC alumni.       Don't miss this opportunity to learn how the highly successful achieved their career goals.   All workshops will be held in 1309 James Hall on the following dates:  Tuesday, September 14, 6-7:30 p.m. Thursday, September 16, 12:30-2 p.m. Tuesday, October 5, 6-7:30 p.m. Thursday, October 7, 12:30-2 p.m. Tuesday, November 2, 6-7:30 p.m. Thursday, November 11, 12:30-2 p.m. Tuesday, December 7, 12:30-2 p.m.  Remember, this workshop is required for students to get an alumni mentor, to join the Magner Alumni & Student Professional Networking Group on Linkedin, and to participate in any student/alumni networking events.  Register on the WebCentral portal at http://portal.brooklyn.edu via the Career Tab.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

from_: BC in China Study Abroad Program <CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Second Open House for CUNY-BC Winter 2010-11 in China Program
message: Join us for an open house for the Winter 2010-11 Study Abroad in China Program on any of the following dates:  Wednesday, September 15 Thursday, September 16 Tuesday, September 21  All open houses run from 12:30 to 1:30 p.m., in 3439 Boylan Hall.   Winter 2010-11 Study Abroad in China=20 Tentative Trip Dates: December 29, 2010-January 23, 2011  This four-week program is an inexpensive way to travel and study in China, during which students visit five of the most famous Chinese cities (Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou and Shanghai) and take side trips to Hong Kong, Tibet, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii) or Yellow Mountain.  For details (photos, comments, FAQs, etc.), visit the program's website at:=20 http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china/   Students may choose 3 to 6 credits of study from the following: 1. History 3534: Revolutionary China=20 2. Core 3206: Development of the Silk Road 3. Business 3175: Asian Business=20 4. Chinese 1010: Beginners Chinese, and Chinese 1020: Intermediate Chinese=20 5. Speech 1619: Intercultural Communication=20 6. Speech 2623: Business & Professional Communication (cross-cultural perspectives)=20 7. Core 1010: Classical Cultures (China)   Program features: * All courses are taught by Brooklyn College faculty, for CUNY-BC credit. * Group travel to five of the most famous and beautiful Chinese cities: Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou and Shanghai. * Field trips to sites of historical and cultural importance (e.g., Tiananmen Square, the Great Wall, Forbidden City, Summer Palace, Terra Cotta Warriors, ancient city walls, Buddhist temples, Jewish synagogue, Islamic mosques, Suzhou Gardens, silk factory, Cloisonn=E9 factory, the Bund, Shanghai Pudong Financial District and China's Wall Street, etc.). * Experience Chinese culture, interact with local people, get a real feel of Chinese life. * Travel and sightseeing are arranged by professional travel agencies. * Side trips to Hong Kong, Tibet, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii) or Yellow Mountain  =20 Total estimated program cost: only $2,898, which includes: * Round-trip international tickets (New York to Beijing; Shanghai to New York)=20 * Transportation within and between Chinese cities=20 * Nice hotels in all cities=20 * Admission tickets to scenic spots=20   Eligibility: 1. CUNY undergraduate and graduate students, or=20 2. Students from any other colleges in the United States  STOCS scholarships and financial aid are available for qualified students.  Application deadline: October 15, 2010 (first come, first served)   For more information about the program:=20 * Visit the program website: http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china. * E-mail Professor Lu at CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu. * Call 718.951.5225 (ask for Sonia Garrick).   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Late add and drop period ends Wednesday September 15
message: Dear Students,  Please be advised that the late add period for Fall 2010 ends Wednesday, September 15. To late add a class you must obtain the approval of the instructor and department chairperson on a late add form. This form must be taken to the Enrollment Services Center for actual registration.  Absolutely no late adds will be granted after September 15.  September 15 is also the last day to drop a course without a grade.   September 16 is the first day to apply for an official withdrawal with a W grade and November 17 is the last day to apply for an official withdrawal with a W grade.    Have a wonderful and productive semester.   Office of the Registrar    ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Cancellation Notice - Fall 2010
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   Your fall 2010 semester tuition payment was not satisfied. According to our records, your account reflected an outstanding balance. As a result of this unsatisfied balance, your classes have been cancelled.    You can re-register with an approved Late-Add form signed by the instructor and department chairperson until September 15, 2010. Both signatures must be obtained prior to registration. Completed Late-Add forms must be submitted to the Enrollment Services Center in the lobby of the West Quad Center. Payment is due immediately upon re-registration.   If you need further information, please call 718-951-5200, e-mail us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu, or visit us in the lobby of the West Quad Center. subject: NYPIRG General Interest Meeting
message: On Thursday, Sept. 23, at 12:15 p.m. in the Amersfort Lounge, Student Center, the Brooklyn College New York Public Interest Research Group (NYPIRG) will be holding our general interest meeting. Students who work with NYPIRG:   * lead campaigns to keep CUNY tuition low and will work to make textbooks affordable;  * travel to Albany and visit the offices of elected officials to pressure them about the need to preserve New York's natural beauty while fighting against unsustainable energy policies at the state and local level;   * form coalitions of students to collect food and clothing to donate around the holiday season to improve the lives of some of the 38,000 people living in homeless shelters in New York City;  * work to end the gridlock in our state government and ensure that the voices of students are heard;  * help individuals find justice by providing general consumer counseling and assistance through NYPIRG's Small Claims Action Center;  * protect the public by vigorously researching instances of corporate abuse;  * and much more!  If you would like to find out more about an organization with a 37-year history of success and to start ensuring that the voices of students are heard and taken seriously, attend our general interest meeting.  We look forward to seeing you there!  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Free Photoshop /  Illustrator Workshops
message: Photoshop / Illustrator Workshops  The Brooklyn College Library Office of Academic Information Technologies (AIT) presents intensive hands-on free technology workshops featuring Adobe Photoshop and Adobe Illustrator.   These workshops are open to all Brooklyn College students, staff and faculty.   If you have any questions, contact us at extension 4672 or via e-mail, librarycafe@brooklyn.cuny.edu; or visit http://ait.brooklyn.cuny.edu/librarycafe/home.htm   Beginner's Adobe Photoshop: Get Those Photos Going You can showcase your photos with Adobe Photoshop, a program that's easy to learn and provides powerful, industry-standard, image-editing tools with which you can produce sophisticated graphics, photos and Web content. This beginner's session will give you hands-on instruction on how to create and manipulate images and artwork quickly and easily. If you can use a computer to open, save and close files, you can learn Photoshop!   Friday, Sept. 24  2:30-4 p.m.  383 Library   Adobe Photoshop Open Session: Bring Your Own Projects Need help with a project? In this open-session workshop, bring in your beginner or advanced digital photo projects and our Photoshop experts will work side by side with you, focusing on your specific Photoshop needs. Achieve the results you are looking for with one-on-one help.   Tuesday, Oct. 12 1-2:15 p.m. 383 Library   Beginner Illustrator: Vector Images The course is intended for the user who wishes to use Adobe Illustrator to construct vector illustrations and type effects in order to create custom graphics for a variety of creative solutions using Illustrators' multiplicity of tools.  Thursday, Oct. 21 1-2:15 p.m. 383 Library   Illustrator Open Session: Bring Your Own Projects Need help with a project? In this open-session workshop, bring in your beginner or advanced projects and our Illustrator experts will work side by side with you focusing on your specific needs. Achieve the results you are looking for with one-on-one help.  Friday, Nov. 5 2:30-4 p.m. 383 Library  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Magner Center Offers Jobs and Internships to BC Students
message: Dear Student,  Start now and become the prospective employee that all employers want to hire.   The Magner Center for Career Development and Internships is once again offering a series of superb career and skills related activities this semester. Our workshops and programs are designed to get you the best internships, mentors, professional skills training, resume advice and career counseling available today.  Workshops include Finding the Right Major and Career, Job Search, Building Professional Relationships, The Nuts and Bolts of Internships, Professional Skills Training, Alumni Career Roundtables and more. In addition, the Magner Center provides you with career technologies such as:    * eRecruiting, to find jobs and internships fast, * Optimal Resume, to help you create a top-notch professional resume, * the Alumni Career Network, to locate a successful BC alum as a mentor, * Internships.com, to generate invaluable internship opportunities that lead to real careers, * computerized career assessments that will set you on the right career path early on, and * webinars designed to keep you in touch with the latest jobs, internships and career advice.   Register with the Magner Center and its workshops via the Career Tab on the BC portal, https://portal.brooklyn.edu.  The Fall 2010 Magner Workshop Schedule has been added for your convenience. Take a look and register for the workshop and activity that's best for you by visiting http://info.brooklyn.cuny.edu/confluence/download/attachments/2588751/Magner+Center+Workshop+Schedule+fall+2010+v4+_08+26_.pdf.  Respond to this e-mail if you have any career questions or concerns.  Robert M. Oliva Director Magner Center for Career Development and Internships  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject:
Study Abroad India: Documentary Production and Cultural Studies -
 Winter 2011
message: Study Abroad India:  Documentary Production and Cultural Studies  (Film,  TVR)   The Brooklyn College Study Abroad India course is a 21 day program offering a meaningful combination of lectures, field trips, documentary production work and sightseeing.  For further information about the program please review our web site:    http://studyabroad.brooklyn.cuny.edu/india/Welcome.html  Study Abroad India will provide Brooklyn College students with a rewarding, life transforming experience that complements any academic program.   During the 2011 Winter Intercession program students will visit  both rural and urban South India, including Chennai, Madurai, Dindigul, Ambathurai, and Bangalore.   There will be numerous opportunities to interact with Indian university and college students.   Applications are due in Professor Danto's office on or before October 15, 2010.  All applications must be completed properly.  Applications should be mailed to the Brooklyn College Film Department: 2900 Bedford Ave. 217 Field House Building Brooklyn, NY 11210 or faxed to 718-951 4733 / 718-951 4559. Letters of recommendation may be forwarded separately.  Acceptance into the program will be announced by October 22, 2010.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Learn about Exciting Careers in Foreign and Civil Service
message: Dear Students,    Thomas Armbruster, U.S. Diplomat, United States Department of State, will present exciting details on preparing for a career in Foreign and Civil affairs. If you are interested in working and living overseas this is a must for you to attend.  This is a once in a lifetime opportunity. message: Dear Brooklyn College Student:  It's never too early to start thinking about whether or not a graduate degree should be in your future. Here at Brooklyn College, we offer more than 60 programs in business, education, science, and the humanities and social sciences. subject: Application Deadline for CUNY-BC Winter 2010-11 in China Program
message: Winter 2010-11 Study Abroad in China=20  Application Deadline: October 15  See the new Beijing and the new China after the Olympics! Join us for this inexpensive way to travel and study in China, tentatively scheduled for Dec. 29, 2010-Jan. 23, 2011.  The four-week program visits five famous Chinese cities--Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou and Shanghai--with side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain or Tibet.  For details, photos, comments, FAQs, etc., check the program's website at: http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china/   Students may choose 3 to 6 credits of study from the following:  1.  History 3534: Revolutionary China 2.  Core 3206: Development of the Silk Road 3.  Business 3175: Asian Business 4.  Chinese 1010: Beginners Chinese; Chinese 1020: Intermediate Chinese=20 5.  Speech 1619: Intercultural Communication=20 6.  Speech 2623: Business & Professional Communication (cross-cultural perspectives)=20   Program Features:  * All courses are taught by Brooklyn College faculty, for CUNY-BC credit. * Group travel to five of the most famous and beautiful Chinese cities: Beijing, Xi'an, Nanjing, Suzhou/Hangzhou and Shanghai. * Field trips to sites of historical and cultural importance (e.g., TianAnMen Square, the Great Wall, Forbidden City, Summer Palace, Terra Cotta Warriors, ancient city walls, Buddhist temples, Jewish synagogue, Islamic mosques, Suzhou Gardens, silk factory, cloisonn=E9 factory, the Bund, etc.). * Experience Chinese culture and interact with local people to get a real feel of Chinese life. * Travel and sightseeing are arranged by professional travel agencies. * Side trips to Hong Kong, Sanya (Oriental Hawaii), Yellow Mountain or Tibet. =20  Total Estimated Program Cost: only $2,898, which includes:  1. round-trip international tickets (New York to Beijing; Shanghai to New York), 2. transportation within and between the Chinese cities, 3. nice hotels in all the cities in China, and 4. admission tickets to the scenic spots.   Eligibility:  1. CUNY undergraduate and graduate students, 2. students from any other U.S. college, and 3. CUNY faculty, staff and alumni.  =20 STOCS scholarships and financial Aid are available for qualified students.  If you need financial aid for the trip, make an appointment immediately with the Financial Aid Office in the West Quad Center.   For more information:  1. Visit the program website: http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc-china. 2. E-mail Professor Lu at CUNYinChina@brooklyn.cuny.edu. 3. Call 718.951.5000 ext 3275 (ask for Sonia Garrick).  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject:
Fall 2010 Martin and Syma Mendelsohn Lectureship in International
 Relations
message: Dear Brooklyn College student,  Brooklyn College is pleased to announce the fall 2010 Martin and Syma Mendelsohn Lectureship in International Relations, November 9 from 2:30-3:30 in the Gold Room of the Student Center.    Dr. Christian Prosl, Austrian Ambassador to the United State, will deliver the lecture, titled "Austria, the EU, the US and beyond."   Dr. Christian Prosl has been Ambassador of Austria to the United States in Washington, DC since May 2009. From 2003-2006 he served as Austrian Ambassador to Germany.  Prosl studied Law and French at the University of Vienna and pursued International Studies in Geneva. From 1973 to 1977 he was working at the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) in Burkina Faso and Rwanda. After joining the Foreign Service in 1977 he was assigned to the Austrian Embassy in London, and from 1981-1988 Dr. Prosl held several positions at the Austrian Embassy in Washington, DC. From 1991-1955 he served as Austrian Consul General in Los Angeles. His political career also includes serving as Deputy Secretary General for Foreign Affairs, Director of the Department on Western and Northern Europe and Director General of the Section on Legal and Consular Affairs at the Austrian Ministry for Foreign Affairs.   If you wish to attend, please respond to Ms. Helen Brereton (Brereton@brooklyn.cuny.edu).    Sincerely, Dean Donna F. Wilson  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Skills for Surviving your Turbulent Twenties
message: Dear Student,  Your twenties are going to be filled with big changes, real world challenges and new responsibilities.  It's the time in your life where you must decide who you are, what you want and where you're going after college.  Author and entrepreneur Marcos Salazar will discuss the trials and tribulations you will face during your twenties.  He'll share his insights into how you can successfully transition and thrive during your most turbulent young adult years. subject: Free Federal Job/Internship and Resume Building
message: Dear Student,  The federal government is offering two informative job and internship webinars through the Magner Center at Brooklyn College. The webinars will address current internship and full-time job opportunities with the government. Both webinars offer practical methods of researching, finding and applying for the job and internship that fits you and your career aspirations. This is a rare opportunity, so take advantage of it!  As an added bonus, the Magner Center is offering a webinar on using the social media sidebar on Optimal Resume. Think seriously about taking advantage of all three webinars.    Federal Internships: Find and Apply for Summer Internships in 2011 Wednesday, Oct. 20 Webinar start time: 5 p.m. 1309 James Hall  This webinar, a product of the Partnership for Public Service's Making the Difference campaign, is for students interested in finding and applying for federal internships for Summer 2011 as well as for advisers looking for more information about federal opportunities to share with their students. During this session, we will highlight a number of exciting internships across government, and show you how to research, find and apply for an internship that's right for you. (As this is a webinar, students must be on time. No students will be admitted once the webinar begins.)  Register at: https://portal.brooklyn.edu via the Career Tab.   Federal Jobs: Find and Apply for Full-Time Work in 2011 Tuesday, Oct. 26 Webinar start time: 5 p.m. 1309 James Hall  This webinar, a product of the Partnership for Public Service's Making the Difference campaign, is for students interested in finding and applying for full-time jobs with the federal government as well as for those advisers looking for more information about federal opportunities to share with their students. During this session, we will highlight a number of exciting full-time jobs across government, and show you how to research, find and apply for a job that's right for you. (As this is a webinar, students must be on time. No students will be admitted once the webinar begins.)  Register at: https://portal.brooklyn.edu via the Career Tab    Optimal Resume Job Seeker Training: Using the Social Media Sidebar Wednesday, Oct. 27 Webinar start time: 1 p.m.  This training session is open for career counselors and their student population. The training will be via your computer with NO phone option--you only need Internet connectivity and speakers in order to view and hear the presentation. If you have any questions during the training, you will have the opportunity to type those questions into the question area.  The webinar link is: https://www2.gotomeeting.com/register/127452067  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Be Your Own Boss: Freelancers' Career Forum for the Arts
message: Dear Student,   Tired of clocking in and losing out?   Want to pursue creative, fulfilling work on your own time and also make a living in the process?    Don't miss this very special workshop sponsored by the Magner Center!   Freelancers' Career Forum: The Creative Arts  Tuesday, October 26 12:15-2:15 p.m. Gold Room, 6th floor, Student Center  Panelists from several freelance fields will offer tips, advice, how-to's and everything else you will need to pursue a freelance career. If you are a freelance first-timer interested in becoming a creative professional, then this workshop is for you.   Panelists include:  * Dan DiDio, Writer/Co-Publisher of DC Comics (Superman, Batman etc.)  * Wendy Goodman, Video Journalist for NYDailyNews.com * Kaitlyn Newman, Volunteer Coordinator, Freelancers' Union  * Sarah Alden, Musician, Teaching Artist with Brooklyn Conservatory of Music and Brooklyn Arts Council * Bill Williams, Acting Coach, Director and Teacher  **Refreshments will be served.**  **The first 20 registered students to arrive will receive a free book!**   **All students will receive a free copy of the Professional Skills Handbook.**  Register at https://portal.brooklyn.edu via the Career Tab.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Tow Center for the Performing Arts Takes Its First Step
message: Construction on the temporary or "swing" space for the Conservatory of Music and the Theater Department within Roosevelt Hall Extension will begin this Tuesday, October 26.  Department classrooms and facilities will be clearly marked and directional signage will be posted to help guide students, faculty, and staff.  Demolition of the interior spaces will begin either Thursday, October 28 or Friday, October 29.  The College community and the contractors will share corridors so we ask that for everyone's safety, please follow construction signage and the occasional, but necessary, requests by workmen to detour or move away from construction activities.  To avoid unnecessary disruptions of classes and offices, we have requested that the contractors schedule any noise-producing work for the off hours.  The Roosevelt Hall swing space--expected to be completed by the end of the fall semester-will be ready for use by the Theater Department and the Conservatory of Music by the start of the Spring Semester.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Network Your Way to a Great Career
message: Dear Student,  Networking is the key to your career success. Using LinkedIn is a perfect way to link with professionals and peers in your profession. Sign up for this very special workshop and learn how to use LinkedIn to get you to your dream job and career.  Northwestern Mutual Presents: Are you Linked In?  Thursday, Oct. 28 12:30-2 p.m.  1309 James Hall   Kristen DeFilippe of Northwestern Mutual will teach you:   *  why it's so important for college students to use LinkedIn, *  why it is such a critical networking, job search and career development tool, *  how to set up a basic LinkedIn profile, and *  how it connects to the real world job market.    If you already have a profile, you will learn how to use it for successful career networking.  Seats are limited. To register, log on to BC WebCentral at https://portal.brooklyn.edu via the Career Tab.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

from_: "Prof. Yedidyah Langsam, Brooklyn College (Computer and Information Science)" <langsam@sci.brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: [BC] Winter 2011 Intersession
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   October 27, 2010  Registration for the Winter 2010 Intersession begins Tuesday, November 2, 2010. Classes begin January 3rd. Final examinations will be held on January 24th.  Classes offered during the intersession are very intense, however with dedication, the motivated student has an opportunity to accumulate credits in a very short time.  The CIS Department will be offering the following classes:  CORC 1312 Computing: Nature, Power and Limits 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-11:30 AM  CORC 3303 Exploring Robotics 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-12:00 Noon 	MTWTH 6:00 PM-9:45 PM  CORC 3310 Paradoxes & Limits of Knowledge 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-12:00 Noon	(2 sections)  CISC 1110 Introduction to Programming in C++ 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-1:15 PM  CISC 1050  Introduction to Computer Applications 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-11:30 AM  CISC 1590/BUSN 3420 Management Information Systems 	Fully Online  CISC 1597/BUSN 31.7/TVRA 3537 New Media & Business 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-11:30 AM  CISC 2531/BUSN 3430 Operations Management 	MTWTHF 9:00 AM-11:30 AM 	MTWTH 6:00 PM-9:45 PM  For information and description on these courses as well as other information regarding the CIS Department please go to: http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/pub/departments/cis/index.htm  Students are urged to consult with the Undergraduate Deputy Chairs, Professor Moshe Augenstein (day) augenstein@sci.brooklyn.cuny.edu or Professor Joseph Thurm (evening) thurm@sci.brooklyn.cuny.edu, when planning their programs.   Given the present financial realities it is imperative that all students register as soon as possible for courses within the department. As we approach the beginning of the winter intersession, courses with low registration may be cancelled by the college's administration. Please do not wait until the last moment to register-the course you desire may no longer be available!   Sincerely,   Professor Yedidyah Langsam Chairperson  ------------------------------------------------------------ You received this message because you are registered in a course or enrolled in a program in the following Brooklyn College department: Computer and Information Science  You can manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts in BC WebCentral @ http://portal.brooklyn.edu.  Look for the "BC Student Email Subscriptions" channel on the "My Info" tab.  Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000  		This email was sent to: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN <jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com>

subject: Martin and Syma Mendelsohn Lectureship in International Relations
message: Dear Brooklyn College student,  Brooklyn College is pleased to announce the fall 2010 Martin and Syma Mendelsohn Lectureship in International Relations, November 9 from 2:30-3:30 in the MAROON ROOM of the Student Center (please note change in venue).    Dr. Christian Prosl, Austrian Ambassador to the United State, will deliver the lecture, titled "Austria, the EU, the US and beyond."   Dr. Christian Prosl has been Ambassador of Austria to the United States in Washington, DC since May 2009. From 2003-2006 he served as Austrian Ambassador to Germany.  Prosl studied Law and French at the University of Vienna and pursued International Studies in Geneva. From 1973 to 1977 he was working at the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) in Burkina Faso and Rwanda. After joining the Foreign Service in 1977 he was assigned to the Austrian Embassy in London, and from 1981-1988 Dr. Prosl held several positions at the Austrian Embassy in Washington, DC. From 1991-1955 he served as Austrian Consul General in Los Angeles. His political career also includes serving as Deputy Secretary General for Foreign Affairs, Director of the Department on Western and Northern Europe and Director General of the Section on Legal and Consular Affairs at the Austrian Ministry for Foreign Affairs.   If you want to attend this lecture, you must reserve a seat by responding to Ms. Helen Brereton (Brereton@brooklyn.cuny.edu).    Sincerely, Dean Donna Wilson  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Theatre Development Fund Membership Offier
message: Dear Student,  I am pleased to announce a new partnership that has begun this year between Brooklyn College and the Theatre Development Fund, a New York not-for-profit organization, dedicated to enabling diverse audiences to attend live theater, music and dance in venues throughout New York City. As a part of this partnership, Brooklyn College students will be offered a $10 annual membership to TDF, a savings of $20. Here are the benefits of membership as published on the TDF website, www.tdf.org:  "TDF membership is your ticket to the performing arts at affordable prices. Our members enjoy access to hundreds of Broadway, Off-Broadway, music and dance productions each year for only $11 to $39 a ticket. Additionally, we've just launched a new service for our members, 'Off-Off @ $9,' where dozens of Off-Off-Broadway productions are available to you for only $9 a ticket."    Given the current prices of Broadway theater and New York Philharmonic tickets, if you go to only one performance a year you would be saving money. I hope you will consider taking advantage of this partnership, which will enable you to more affordably enjoy great performances from our city's most distinguished cultural institutions.  For additional information and instructions on how to become a TDF member, visit http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc/spotlite/tdf/brooklynstudents.htm  Enjoy, Provost Tramontano  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Fall 2010 Withdrawal Deadline November 17
message: The last day to withdraw from any Fall 2010 course is November 17, 2010. Absolutely no withdrawals will be allowed after November 17, 2010.  When you withdraw from courses, a W grade will stay on your transcript but it will not affect your GPA. If you are receiving financial aid, you are advised to speak to a financial aid advisor before withdrawing from courses.   To withdraw online:  You may withdraw from any course(s) online via WebCentral (https://portal.brooklyn.edu).   To withdraw onsite:  You may submit a withdrawal form in the Enrollment Services Center.  Withdrawal and other registrar services offered at the Enrollment Services Center are temporarily located in the Registrar's Office on the third floor of the West Quad Center.  Please note that the Registrar's Office will be open until 8:00 PM on Wednesday, November 17 to service students who wish to submit the withdrawal form in person.  The following students may not withdraw online and must obtain the signature of a counselor from the respective department before returning the completed withdrawal form to the Registrar's Office.  * First semester freshmen, second semester freshmen, first semester transfer students and students on academic probation must report to the Center for Academic Advisement and Student Success (3207 Boylan Hall).   * SEEK students must report to the SEEK Department (2208 Boylan Hall).  * ESL students must report to the ESL Department (1414 Ingersoll Hall).  * TOCA students must report to the TOCA Department (3219 Boylan Hall).  * Students withdrawing from English 1 must report to the English Department (2308 Boylan Hall).          ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: CELL PHONE / I POD THEFTS VICINITY OF CAMPUS RD.
message: This office has become aware of what appears to be an increase in incidents involving the "snatching" of cell phones and I pods in the vicinity of Campus Road and the Junction area. Even though the majority of reported incidents do not involve the Brooklyn College Community, it is important to have this information to avoid being a victim. Persons travelling to and from campus should, if at all possible, avoid talking on cell phones and avoid wearing ear buds, since it appears that perpetrators target those individuals. Be aware of your surroundings at all times and travel in pairs or more, if possible. Utilize the College's Shuttle which travels around the campus perimeter and to the local subways. During the upcoming Holiday Season, which traditionally has shown an increase in these types of crimes, take steps to increase your personal safety. Visit our Web Site at "www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc/offices/security" and see our guide on Personal Safety Tips.

subject: Announcing The Princeton Review's 2010-11 Student Survey
message: The Princeton Review is inviting you to participate in a survey about our school. Your responses will help determine our ranking in The Princeton Review's new edition of its Best Colleges for 2012.    To take the survey, go to http://survey.review.com/ss/.  Every student who completes the survey will be entered in a raffle to win an Apple iPad mobile digital device. The Princeton Review will choose 10 winners at random.   Thank you for your support and helping Brooklyn College.   Milga Morales Vice President for Student Affair  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. message: Dear Students,  The Spring 2011 Schedule of Classes is now available online at http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/pub/registration.htm, and in the left-hand Resources menu in your WebCentral Portal view. subject: Spring 2011 TuitionPay Payment Plan
message: Beginning November 30th payment plans are available for the Spring 2011 semester!  TuitionPay is an easy and convenient way to break down your tuition expenses into interest free, easy to manage monthly installments. There is an $18 enrollment fee; to enroll or for more information, please visit www.tuitionpay.com/cuny. You must register for a plan by your payment due date as designated in the Schedule of Classes to avoid course cancellation. Please note that it will take 24 - 48 hours for the plan to appear on your Brooklyn College account. You can log on to WebSIMS via the WebCentral portal to verify that your plan has been posted to your account.  The tuition payment plan, TuitionPay is not available for the Winter Intersession.    If you would like assistance or have questions please call Sallie Mae at (866) 267-2869.  Please note that this e-mail is for informational purposes and is not an indication that you did not pay your bill.   Thank you.  Office of the Bursar/Student Payment Services    ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Televised Basketball Doubleheader This Thursday in West Quad Center
message: The Brooklyn College Bulldogs Men's and Women's Basketball teams will be hosting City Tech in their first conference doubleheader of the season on Thursday, Dec. 2.  Students from the Department of Television and Radio will be filming the contests, which will air citywide on a later date on CUNY TV.  The women's game begins at 5 p.m.; the men's game starts at 7:30 p.m. Admission is free. Come out and support your Bulldogs!  For more information, contact the Brooklyn College Athletics office.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: BC Feedback (Student Evaluation of the Faculty)
message: BC FEEDBACK FOR FALL 2010 IS ONLINE  You've taken the class, you've done the work... Now tell us what you think!  We want to hear your opinion... In your own words!!  *   *   *   *   *   *   *   *  This semester the BC Feedback period will run from Nov. 30 through Dec. 29. Because it's completely online, you can sit at home with a cup of coffee, jump on a computer at the Library Caf=E9, or take a quick break at work to let us know what you think!  By evaluating the professors who taught you this semester, you'll provide a great service to your fellow students and the college at large.  Plus, only participants completing all of their evaluations receive these great benefits:  * Lottery prizes--a chance to win cash prizes of $250, $100 and $50.  * Early notification of course grades via eGrade--in some instances up to 15 days before grades are posted!  * Early access to your fellow students' ratings and comments about their professors and courses in time for Spring 2011 semester program changes!  * The opportunity to play an important role in enhancing academic excellence at Brooklyn College.  Student evaluations are a key component of the college's review of faculty performance. Your feedback will help faculty and departments provide the best possible instruction. All responses are completely anonymous, and your identity will not be associated with your evaluations.  It's easy and only takes a few minutes! Just log on to the WebCentral Portal (https://portal.brooklyn.edu). Look for the BC Feedback tab for the evaluation links and status page.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: Tragic Death of Brooklyn College Student
message: Dear Brooklyn College community,  I write with great sadness to inform you of the tragic death of one of our students, Moshe Berkowitz, who was the innocent victim of a fatal car crash when his car was struck by another motorist early this morning.  I know that many of Moshe's friends on campus are grieving his loss.  Our hearts go out to them and especially to the members of his family.   President Karen L. Gould    ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. subject: Art Award Announcement
message: 2011 LIBRARY ART AWARD  Discover the Museum Inside the Library  Explore the Library's Internationally Recognized Artworks  Which work of art in the library inspires you? You may respond to any work of art in the library in writing, art, music or film. An undergraduate and graduate winner will be selected by a panel of judges. Each will receive a $500 award.   For more information, go to the library's website and click on Art Collection, or visit http://dewey.brooklyn.cuny.edu/library/art/    Art Award Rules  1. The prize is open to all Brooklyn College undergraduate and graduate students who possess a valid ID. The prize is $500 for the undergraduate winner and $500 for the graduate winner.   2. Your name, telephone number, address, e-mail, and the artist and the title of the work of art in the library you are responding to must be attached to your submission. Joint submissions should include this information for each person. If a joint entry is awarded, the prize money will be divided equally among the persons listed on the information sheet attached to the submitted entry.  3. Each person may submit only one entry.   4. Submissions may be presented in any medium: Essays, poems, short stories, musical compositions, photography and artwork (still or moving) are welcome.  5. The submission should be sent electronically to Professor Miriam Deutch, miriamd@brooklyn.cuny.edu. Works on canvas/paper, sculptures or other media should be brought to 412 Library on Monday-Thursday, 9 a.m.-5 p.m., and Friday, 9 a.m.-1 p.m.  6. All entries must be received by Jan. 31, 2011.       7. Works will be judged by a panel of judges, including two faculty members from the Library as well as faculty members from the departments of Art, Music and English.  8. The judges' decision is final.   9. The awards will be announced in March 2011.  ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000
