subject: Brooklyn College Registration Appointment Reminder
message: Brooklyn College                             e-ALERT                            December 12, 2010         Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN,       Just a reminder that you may register for the Spring 2011 courses starting December 14 at 10:30 am.          Students who are scheduled to graduate, receive registration appointments.  Some students may need to take a course or two to fulfill their graduation requirements.  If you are graduating, and do not need additional courses, please disregard this e-mail reminder.        To register on-line using WebSIMS, simply point your browser to the BC WebCentral at http://portal.brooklyn.edu. WebSIMS channel will be available on "eServices" tab. You can also use "WebSIMS" shortcut link in the left sidebar regardless of which tab is currently active. If this is your first time using WebSIMS, please read the browser requirements carefully on the subsequent screen and feel free to access the on-line usage instruction once in WebSIMS.         WebSIMS is not only a great way to register, it also lets you view your transcript, view your financial info and perform many other tasks quickly and easily from anywhere on the Internet.       If you do not have access to a suitable Internet accessible PC, you may use one of the many public-access lab PCs on campus.       Reminder... if you've not already done so, please enroll for e-Grades which will ensure that your term grades are emailed to the email ID of your choice as soon as they are submitted by your instructor.  Your e-Grades subscription will also allow the college to send you other helpful alerts and information, like this one.  If you'd prefer to receive e-Alerts at another email account, simply register it in BC WebCentral.       If you note any problems or glitches, please report them to the Registrar at (718) 951-5441 or via e-mail to websims@brooklyn.cuny.edu  ------------------------------------------------------------  ------------------------------------------------------------ This message is sent from an unattended mailbox. subject: Save Time -- Renew Online!
message: Dear Students:  We know this is a busy time of year for you. So if you don't have time to come in to the library to return or renew your books, renew online!    If you haven't renewed your books three times already (this is the maximum number of renewals), just follow these instructions:   *. Go to the library website, http://library.brooklyn.cuny.edu. Click on Catalog. Click on My Account / Renew (top right of page).  * Enter your 14-digit library barcode (beginning with 2) in the textbox marked Barcode. (Do not enter spaces or dashes.) As your password, enter your 14-digit library barcode again. (NOTE: Your library barcode will remain your password unless you change it.) Then click on Log In.  If you have any difficulty, just contact the Circulation Desk at 718.951.5335, and we will walk you through the process.    Best of luck on your exams! from_: "Louise Hainline, Dean of Research and Graduate Studies" <sems@brooklyn.cuny.edu>
subject: Earn and Learn this summer - Summer Research Externship Database
message: If you are still trying to decide what to do this summer, consider a paid academic research placement. Graduate and some professional schools favor students who have had research experience in the discipline the student is pursuing, the more the better. Doing research with faculty mentors can lead to better letters of recommendation and better insights into how to choose the right graduate program. While this can include working with a Brooklyn College faculty member, doing research at another site as an undergraduate can improve your chances for getting into the best graduate and professional programs.  Fortunately, to recruit students to their graduate schools, many excellent universities offer the opportunity to do research with a faculty member over the summer. These programs typically pay you a stipend, as much as $4000-5000 for the summer, and typically provide funding for housing and travel as well. The shortest ones are 6 weeks and the longest around 10 weeks.  Each year, the NIH MARC program at BC creates a searchable database of many summer externships, posted at: http://www.sci.brooklyn.cuny.edu/research/. You can search by school (pull down menu) or by discipline (search box). If you type in "National Science Foundation", you will get the url for a site at http://www.nsf.gov/crssprgm/reu/reu_search.cfm where you can also search all the NSF Research Experience for Undergraduate programs as many are not included in our database. If you are in the sciences and some social sciences, check that link out as well.   Please note that we do not have any more information about these programs than what appears here. Do not contact us about any specific program's information. You have to contact the program through the contact person or info listed and do your own searching. If a link is broken, email louiseh@brooklyn.cuny.edu and we will try to fix any broken links.   Some tips on using this resource to best advantage:  ** Start as soon as you can, as many of the most competitive programs have deadlines in January and February. You will need letters of recommendation and faculty may not be around during the winter break, so we recommend you check with the professors you would be asking to find out whether they can write you a letter if you need them before next semester. There are plenty of options for later applications as well, but most are no later than March or April.   ** Most applications request a transcript, letters of recommendation and a statement of purpose (to explain your interest in the field, describe prior research experience, and explain your academic goals in the field; it's not a personal historym despite being sometimes called a "personal statement"). If you have never written one of these, the url http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/642/01/ links to one of the many websites with tips on writing the personal statement. We suggest you always have someone experienced read your statement before you submit it.   **  To use the database, type in the name of an academic discipline or subdiscipline or a specific school, and hit "submit" to see what matches your interests. The majority of these opportunities are in the sciences. Search on the discipline or topic of interest. It helps to start with broader search terms and work down to more specific ones. Try several means of searching. The descriptions provided by the programs are used and these are not standardized.   **   In areas outside of science, try searching on terms like "humanities" or "arts". There are fewer of these, but there are some great programs in the database for non-sciences and social sciences.   ** There has also been an increase in programs specifically for students interested in medicine (search "medicine", "premed", "dental"). However, if a program says it is for students interested in "research degrees" or Ph.D's, students who have medical interests will be screened out, so consider this as you choose where to apply.   ** The placements in the database are mostly academic or governmental. If you want a business or professional internship, you should contact the Magner Center.   ** Some listings indicate they are primarily for "under-represented" students, but this term is being broadened, so it can include students who are the first in their families to go to college, or from low-income circumstances, or with disabilities, so be sure to read  carefully what students are eligible to apply for each. It never hurts to email to ask if you are eligible.  ** There are programs for students at all undergraduate levels, including freshmen. Some programs have minimum gpas or other considerations. These are listed with each entry. If nothing appears, the information we had did not include this information, and you should check the with the program.   We have had many students do these summer externships and have had wonderful experiences that have expanded their horizons and improved their credentials at the same time they have earned a stipend that pays more than many summer jobs. We would like more Brooklyn College undergraduates to have this experience. Good luck!   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000

subject: FW: A Letter of Gratitude
message: -----Original Message----- From: bbjacobsohn7@gmail.com [mailto:bbjacobsohn7@gmail.com]  Sent: Thursday, December 16, 2010 2:56 PM To: Chave Jacobsohn Subject: A Letter of Gratitude  Dear my favorite mum,       Firstly I would like to thank you, one for being the greatest mother and two for giving me the ability to have a great vacation. Second, I'm having a great time here in the holy land. I think my friends like me. We just got to the end of our 5th and half blatt gemara. Its got really cold here, I get to wear my coat and sweaters which makes me happy. My happiness makes me hungry. My hungry makes me fat. We don't get to see many zebras. The trip to Eilat was amazing........OMG!!!! I didn't even start to tell you about the trip I'm thanking you for. Well here it goes.................................................................         Jerusalem...Neve Yaakov........Kaminetz.........Shadiker 4.........Yeshiva Lev Aryeh Dormitory 3........12:00        B.B.!!!!!! Wake up... We want to get out of here *(jking I was up for shacris, there's only ten guys who do get up so they waited for me).        I'm getting up I'll be ready in five minutes.        Three hours later...... All right I'm ready  We're all in the car and ready to go. We're off to.....Ramat eshkol to get bagels for lunch and food for a barbeque.        One and a quarter hour later....          Take the tunnel and go straight then just follow the signs and you'll get to Eilat. You can't miss it.         Fifteen minutes later....         We missed the tunnel                  Back on track 3 hours left and will be in eilat            6 hours later... Due to sandstorm and bathroom breaks we are just getting to the Dead Sea. An hour left till Eilat.        Now we're in Eilat and the trip is really starting. Arriving at the we are stunned, such a nice hotel for such a cheap price. We go to the desk to check in. Nope your looking for our other branch, the lady said. Arriving at our actual hotel we are stunned, still from the first hotel it would have been great to stay there. But this place is perfect, five guys in a room with one big bed and a bunkbed. We we're hungry so we went for pizza the only kosher food we could find. Delicious. After eating we went to look for things to do, and found a pyramid that seemed to be a branch of AppleTM. We sure had to check it out, it had huge letters on the top....I-MAX. Turns out it was a place that shows 3-D movies. So went on a roller-coaster that didn't move. After that we decided to call it a night partly due to dizziness. ( P.s. And I know these usually go on the bottom...we davened mincha before we left but had to find a minyan for maariv,we did, in chabad and the did chant yechi adoshen....) Monday.      We awoke early to go to chabad and davened shacris. We waited to have an early lunch of yep that's right,,pizza.then we were off to the oceanarium a beautiful place. We saw sharks get fed and turtles and these real radical fish and this video/ride about scuba diving whale sharks. Or maybe it was scuba divers saving whale sharks idk the seats moved so it was hard to see the screen. Well after that we decided to go a.t.v.ing we found a really awesome place and spent and hour on the quads rippin thru the dessert. It was already getting late so we made a great barbeque compliments to our own chef.  Tuesday: We woke davened went scuba diving and had pizza nothing crazy. What you went scuba diving!!!,!?!?!?!? Oh yeah it was amazing what a great experience you have to go.. Wow words can't explain but they can't thank you. So I would love to thank you mom.  For giving me a great vacation so that I can get back to yeshiva and grow spiritually and mature maturally.                           ThanxX0X0                                   Love !BB!   P.S.S. Also thanx to ta P.S.S.S. I really hope I didn't spend too much......       Sent via BlackBerry from T-Mobile

For information on confirming shipment of multiple orders at once, search on "confirm ship" in seller Help.   - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  HOW TO CANCEL ORDERS   Sellers should have sufficient inventory on hand to fulfill all orders on time. However, in those rare cases when ordered items are not available, please cancel the order promptly. After you cancel the order, Amazon will send the buyer an order cancellation e-mail.  You can cancel orders easily in Manage Orders:  1. In your Seller Account under the "Manage Your Orders" heading, click "View your orders" to find the order you want to cancel.  2. Click the "Cancel order" button next to the order (or below the order if you are looking at an Order Details page).  3. Select the appropriate reason, and then click Submit.  For information on cancelling orders using a feed, search on "cancel multiple orders" in seller Help.   Note that if you have already confirmed shipment of the order, you will no longer be able to cancel it. In that case, you would issue a refund and work with the buyer to arrange a return. For information about refunds, search on "refund orders" in seller Help.  - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  ABOUT YOUR PAYMENT  This transaction will be posted to your Marketplace Payments account after you confirm shipment. Funds in your Marketplace Payments account are automatically disbursed to your bank account every 14 days. After funds are disbursed from your Marketplace Payments account, it can take up to 5 business days for your bank to make the funds available in your checking account.  Please make sure your bank account information is always up to date so there are no delays in disbursements to your bank account. To do so:  1. Go to your Seller Account and click the "Seller Account Information" link in the Settings section.   2. In the Bank Account section, click the Add or Edit button to update your checking account information.

subject: Last chance to review your Fall 2010 professors!
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   There's still time to complete your remaining course evaluations to qualify for the many benefits listed below. The evaluations are online and can be completed anytime today or tomorrow.  To complete your evaluations, just login to WebCentral (http://portal.brooklyn.cuny.edu) and select each of your courses.  The "BC Feedback" tab appears as soon as you login to WebCentral.  If you do not see the "BC Feedback" tab once you log in to BC WebCentral, try the following steps: 1. Click on Customize link in the upper right corner. 2. Choose "Revert to default layout" option.  3. Logout from BC WebCentral and log in again.    Please contact BC WebCentral Support at portal@brooklyn.cuny.edu or at 718-951-5383 if you need additional assistance.   *  *  *  *  *  *  *     We know your time is valuable and to show our appreciation for completing 100% of your evaluations:       +++ You will get early access to your fellow students' rating and comments about their professors and courses in time to make schedule changes for the spring 2011 semester. Other students will NOT have access to this information until late February -- after the drop/add period in spring 2011.    +++ You will have a chance to win cash prizes of $250, $100 and $50.     +++ You will be notified of your course grades as soon as they are submitted by your professors. Students who have not completed 100% of their evaluations will need to wait until at least January 6th.  If you have not yet subscribed to eGrades, you can do it in BC WebCentral.  Just look for the "BC Student Email Subscriptions" link in the Shortcuts menu or on the "My Info" tab.  All student responses are completely anonymous! Thank you for your cooperation and your help in enhancing teaching and learning at Brooklyn College!   Sincerely,  Jerry Mirotznik Associate Provost   		This email was sent to: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN <jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com>

Please note that although your grade has been submitted by your instructor, it may take 5-10 business days for it to appear on your transcript.       Due to new CUNY rules, ABS and FAB grades do not appear on student transcripts. Instead, the ABS grade will automatically be translated into an INC grade in WebSIMS and transcripts, and an internal transcript comment will indicate that the INC was assigned on account of a missed final. This ABS grade will eventually either be changed to a standard grade if you are allowed to take a make-up absentee final exam, or an FIN if that does not occur.         BC's internal systems such as the WebCentral Portal will show the ABS grade until it is resolved. You can verify the ABS status of the course in the WebCentral Portal under the My Info tab, in "My Schedule and Grades" channel. message: As you know ITS had scheduled critical network component upgrades for December 27th. subject: 1098-T Tax Form
message: Dear AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN:   The Office of the University Controller will begin mailing the 2010 1098-T American Opportunity, Hope, and Lifetime Tax Credit Form starting January 31st, 2011. Please allow seven business days to receive the form. To ensure proper and fast delivery of your tax form, please verify that the College has your updated address. Log on to WebSIMS via the WebCentral portal at https://portal.brooklyn.cuny.edu to update/review your address.   Please be advised that if you had TAP and PELL covering your full 2010 tuition, you will not receive a 1098-T tax statement. The 1098-T tax form is provided only to students covering tuition expenses with their own income and/or student loans.   All international and out-of-state students must submit a request for a 1098-T tax form. To request a 2010 1098-T tax form, please email bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu starting January 31, 2011. Please allow 2-7 business days to receive the form.   For further information on the 2010 1098-T tax form, please contact the Office of the Bursar at (718) 951-5200, or email us at bcbursar@brooklyn.cuny.edu.   Thank you.     The Office of the Bursar   ------------------------------------------------------------ To manage your subscription to Brooklyn College eAlerts, please visit https://websql.brooklyn.cuny.edu/ealerts Brooklyn College is located at 2900 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11210. Phone: 718-951-5000  		This email was sent to: AVRAHAM JACOBSOHN <jayjacobsohn@yahoo.com>
